  <text>
    <body>
      <head>A New Handbook of Syriac Literature: Encoding Guidelines and TEI P5 Schema Customization</head>
      <opener>
        This version of the encoding guidelines for <ref target="https://syriaca.org/geo"
          ><title>The Syriac Gazetteer</title></ref> were drafted in 2025 by David A. Michelson,
        William L. Potter, and Daniel L. Schwartz. These guidelines are part of an ongoing community
        effort to develop uniform good practice in describing geographic data using TEI XML. These
        guidelines remain under development and contributions are welcome via pull requests or
        issues submitted to the <ref
          target="https://github.com/srophe/Gaddel/tree/main/documentation/schemas">GitHub
          repository</ref> hosted by <ref target="http://syriaca.org">Syriaca.org</ref>. They are
        licensced under a <ref target="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/">Creative
          Commons Attribution 4.0 International license</ref>. Users may cite the guidelines in this
        way: David A. Michelson, et. al., eds. <title>The Syriac Gazetteer: TEI P5 Customization and
          Encoding Guidelines</title> (Syriaca.org: 2025), <ref
            target="https://github.com/srophe/Gaddel/blob/main/documentation/schemas/syriacaPlaces.odd"
            >https://github.com/srophe/Gaddel/blob/main/documentation/schemas/syriacaPlaces.odd</ref>.
        <!-- Need to update URL to production URL? -->
      </opener>
      
      <divGen type="toc" xml:id="toc"/>
      
      
      <div xml:id="documentation">
        <head>NHSL Encoding Guidelines</head>
        <div xml:id="introduction">
          <head>Introduction</head>
          <p>Welcome to the encoding guidelines for the third edition of <ref
              target="https://syriaca.org/geo"><title>The Syriac Gazetteer</title></ref> (hereafter
              <title>TSG</title>). <title>TSG</title> is a geographical reference work published by
              <ref target="https://syriaca.org"><title>Syriaca.org: The Syriac Reference
                Portal</title></ref> for places relevant to Syriac studies. These guidelines
            describe the methodology used to create <ref target="https://www.tei-c.org">TEI</ref>
            XML files for encoding Syriac geographic data according to the schema implemented by
            Syriaca.org. We have chosen to use the TEI guidelines because they allow a high level of
            detail, citation of sources, and flexibility for representing prose data. We anticipate
            that this schema can be easily adapted for other historical gazetteers and we invite
            comments and suggestions for improvement. </p>
        </div>
        <div xml:id="acknowledgements">
          <head>Acknowledgements</head>
          <p>This present document reuses and adapts from material published published by the Text
            Encoding Initiative as <ref
              target="https://tei-c.org/release/doc/tei-p5-doc/en/html/index.html"><title>TEI:
                Guidelines for Electronic Text Encoding and Interchange</title></ref> in the P5
            release, version 4.9.0 as updated on 24th January 2025 (revision f73186978). The TEI
            guidelines are reused here under the terms of the <ref
              target="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/">Creative Commons Attribution 3.0
              Unported License</ref>.</p>
          <p>The present document is also an update to previous documentation published by
            Syriaca.org. An initial schema and documentation for the first edition of <title>The
              Syriac Gazetteer</title> was designed in 2012-2014 by Thomas Carlson, Tom Elliott,
            David A. Michelson, Winona Salesky, and Daniel L. Schwartz. In 2019, David A. Michelson,
            William L. Potter and Michelle P. Taylor prepared written documentation for the second
            edition of <title>TESG</title>. Portions of the documentation from the first two
            editions have been reused below under the terms of the <ref
              target="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/">Creative Commons Attribution 4.0
              International license</ref>. The current document represents guidelines for the third
            edition of <title>The Syriac Gazetteer</title>.</p>
          <p>In addition, prose and examples have been reused from David A. Michelson, “Using Linked
            Open Data to Model Cultural Heritage Information: The Research Questions and Data
            Structures of the Syriaca.org Knowledge Graph,” in <title>Linked Open Data for the
              Ancient Mediterranean: Structures, Practices, Prospects</title>, edited by Sarah E.
            Bond, Paul Dilley, and Ryan Horne, <title>ISAW Papers</title> 20 (2021), <ref
              target="http://hdl.handle.net/2333.1/69p8d8cc"
              >http://hdl.handle.net/2333.1/69p8d8cc</ref> and from David A. Michelson, et. al.,
            eds. <title>Syriac Manuscripts in the British Library: TEI P5 Customization and Encoding
              Guidelines for Manuscript Description</title> (Syriaca.org: 2024), <ref
              target="https://github.com/srophe/britishLibrary/blob/main/documentation/schema/Syriacamsdesc.html"
              >https://github.com/srophe/britishLibrary/blob/main/documentation/schema/Syriacamsdesc.html</ref>
            under the terms of the <ref target="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/"
              >Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International license</ref>. </p>
        </div>
        <div xml:id="principles">
          <head>General Editorial Principles</head>
          <div xml:id="syriacaDataModel">
            <head>The Seven Core Entities of the Syriaca.org Data Model</head>
            <p><ref target="https://syriaca.org/geo"><title>The Syriac Gazetteer</title></ref>
                (<title>TSG</title>) was conceived as part of a larger project to produce reference
              works (authority files) for the field of Syriac studies. The Syriaca.org data model is
              designed around identifying and describing seven core conceptual entities relevant to
              historical research: <list>
                <item>Places, e.g., the city of Edessa (URI: <ref
                    target="https://syriaca.org/place/78"
                    ><code>http://syriaca.org/place/78</code></ref>)</item>
                <item>Persons, e.g., the author Ephrem the Syrian (URI: <ref
                    target="https://syriaca.org/person/13"
                    ><code>http://syriaca.org/person/13</code></ref>)</item>
                <item>Literary Works, e.g., <title>The Life of Abraham Quidounaya</title> by Ephrem
                  the Syrian (URI: <ref target="http://syriaca.org/work/567"
                      ><code>http://syriaca.org/work/567</code></ref>)</item>
                <item>Bibliographic Items (modern publications), e.g., Robert Murray, <title>Symbols
                    of Church and Kingdom</title> (1975) (URI: <ref
                    target="http://syriaca.org/cbss/M8NJIL53"
                      ><code>http://syriaca.org/cbss/M8NJIL53</code></ref>)</item>
                <item>Subject Headings (thematic keywords related to Syriac Studies), e.g.,
                  “asceticism” (URI: <emph>under development</emph>)</item>
                <item>Manuscripts, e.g., British Library Manuscript Add. 14,451 (URI: <emph>under
                    development</emph>)</item>
                <item>Material Artifacts, e.g., the Edessene Mosaic of Orpheus Taming Wild Animals
                  (URI: <emph>under development</emph>)</item>
              </list></p>
            <p>For each of the above entities, Syriaca.org's primary goal is to publish <q>authority
                files</q>, e.g. reference works which establish a unique identifier for each person,
              place, primary source text, bibliographic citation, keyword, manuscript, and material
              artifact relevant to the field of Syriac studies. The format of the identifier is a
              URI, a technical specification which is described in more detail below; see <ref
                target="#assigningURIs">Assigning Place URIs (Uniform Resource Identifiers)</ref>.
              In these authority files, each entity is an individual abstract concept identified by
              a unique URI. For example, the person known as Ephrem the Syrian is identified by the
              URI: <ref target="http://syriaca.org/person/13">http://syriaca.org/person/13</ref> and
              the city of Edessa where he spent much of his life is identified as <ref
                target="http://syriaca.org/place/78">http://syriaca.org/place/78</ref>. The
              necessity of using unique strings of characters instead of traditional names arises
              from the occurrence of homonymous entities. For example, <title>TSG</title> has
              entries for more than 50 different churches and monasteries each with the name <q>Mar
                Gewargis</q> (St. George). Accordingly, all Syriaca.org URIs are unique—each
              identifying only one conceptual entity. Thus, every <q>Church of Mar Gewargis</q> is
              assigned a separate URI.</p>
            <p>Syriaca.org URIs are not merely random strings of text and numbers; they are HTTP
              URIs, meaning that each URI is also a URL (a Uniform Resource Locator, e.g. an HTTP
              address). Thus, Syriaca.org’s URI for Ephrem the Syrian, <ref
                target="http://syriaca.org/person/13"
                ><code>http://syriaca.org/person/13</code></ref>, is also a valid HTTP address. The
              benefit of using HTTP URIs is that these URIs are <q>self-descriptive</q> in that each
              URI is also an HTTP link to a web document describing or defining the concept
              identified by the URI. Although perhaps obvious to state, the web document which is
              returned from a Syriaca.org URI is only a definition of the concept named by the URI,
              not the entity itself (thus the address <ref target="http://syriaca.org/place/78"
                  ><code>http://syriaca.org/place/78</code></ref> does <emph>not</emph> allow one to
              download the real-world city of Edessa, but a web page describing that city!).</p>
            <p>In the Syriaca.org data model, each URI represents a conceptual thing with a mental
              existence related to, but not reducible to, its historical or physical manifestation.
              Syriaca.org adopted this broad definition so that mythological and other ahistorical
              persons, places, and concepts can be assigned URIs. For example, the concept
              identified by the URI <ref target="http://syriaca.org/person/13"
                >http://syriaca.org/person/13</ref> identifies not only the historical person Ephrem
              the Syrian, but also the supra-historical hagiographical and pseudepigraphal
              traditions about him. Following this same logic, any historical concept can be
              described in the Syriaca.org URI model, even if its historical existence was only in
              the cultural imaginary.</p>
            <p><title>TSG</title> is the Syriaca.org publication dedicated to describing places and
              is responsible for assinging URIs to individual place entities in the Syriaca.org data
              model. Descriptions of places in <title>TSG</title> can also refer to URIs for any of
              the seven entities, thus a <title>TSG</title> record for a particular place may define
              that place in relation to other places, as well as to persons, bibliography, etc. In
              each instance, these relationships will be encoded in the <title>TSG</title> record as
              references to Syriaca.org URIs. Taken as a whole, the entire Syriaca.org dataset of
              linked URIs forms a "knowledge graph" or a map of relationships between URIs from the
              seven core entitites. In the example of Ephrem the Syrian
                (<code>http://syriaca.org/person/13</code>) and the city of Edessa
                (<code>http://syriaca.org/place/78</code>) the relationship between these two
              entities is part of the Syriaca.org knowledge graph. </p>
          </div>
          <div xml:id="placeConcept">
            <head>The Concept of Place in <title>TSG</title></head>
            <p><title>TSG</title> is a geographical reference work (in library science terms, an
                <q>authority file</q>) published by Syriaca.org to identify and describe places
              relevant to Syriac studies. The concept of distinct place is the distinguishing
              criterion for each entry in <title>TSG</title>. Each record in <title>TSG</title>
              represents a single place that can be disambiguated from other places. Each place is a
              unique conceptual entity with a mental existence related to, but not reducible to, its
              physical manifestation. The purpose of each record (and thus each XML file) is to
              provide information which describes the place identified with that record.</p>
            <div xml:id="assigningURIs">
              <head>Assigning Place URIs (Uniform Resource Identifiers)</head>
              <p>Each place in <title>TSG</title> is assigned a unique indentifier. Because place
                names can be overlapping, ambiguous, or homonymous, this unique indentifier is the
                essential element of every TSG record. Both users and the database itself rely on
                this identifier to disambiguate place records.</p>
              <p>The format of identifier used in <title>TSG</title> is that of a URI (Uniform
                Resource Identifier), a technical standard established by the <ref
                  target="https://www.w3.org/TR/webarch/#identification">World Wide Web Consortium
                  (W3C)</ref>. In <title>TSG</title>, the URIs have the following format:
                  <code>http://syriaca.org/place/{\d+}</code> (where <code>{\d+}</code> signifies a
                unique string of digits). For example, the city of <ref
                  target="https://syriaca.org/place/78">Edessa</ref> is assigned the following URI:
                  <code>http://syriaca.org/place/78</code>. Syriaca.org URIs are not merely random
                strings of text and numbers; they are HTTP URIs, meaning that each URI is also a URL
                (a Uniform Resource Locator) that can be used as a web address leading to a file
                which provides a definition of the entity associated with the URI.</p>
              <p>Or in simple terms, <title>TSG</title> assigns the unique URI
                  <code>http://syriaca.org/place/78</code> as an ID number for the concept of the
                city of Edessa, but that URI is also a working URL which will load the
                  <title>TSG</title> record describing the city of Edessa (see <ref
                  target="https://syriaca.org/place/78">https://syriaca.org/place/78</ref>).</p>
              <p>In each <title>TSG</title> record, this URI is encoded in an <gi>idno</gi> element
                toward the end of the XML document. For a discussion of how to endcode the assigned
                URI as an <gi>idno</gi> element, see the documentation section below on <ref
                  target="#idno">Identifiers (<gi>indo</gi>)</ref> .</p>
            </div>
            <div xml:id="scope">
              <head>Scope of <title>TSG</title></head>
              <p>In terms of including places in <title>TSG</title>, the editors interpret the scope
                of “places relevant to Syriac Studies” in a maximal rather than restrictive sense,
                thus <title>TSG</title> is meant to include places named in Syriac texts (such as
                  <ref target="https://syriaca.org/place/326">Ḥarqel — ܚܪܩܠ</ref>), places of
                interest to scholars who work on Syriac history and culture (such as <ref
                  target="https://syriaca.org/place/77">Dura-Europos</ref>), places where
                scholarship on Syriac is being produced (such as <ref
                  target="https://syriaca.org/place/593">Japan</ref>), and contemporary places
                relevant to the modern Syriac heritage communities. There are no chronological or
                spatial constraints on what may be included in <title>TSG</title>. At least in
                theory, any type or size of place could be represented in the geographic database,
                from large empires to single churches or a particular named city gate. Map
                coordinates are provided for some places, but the database also includes places
                which are not located or even locatable. Mythological and other ahistorical places
                are also included in the database.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div xml:id="bibliographicCitation">
            <head>Bibliographic Citation Requirement</head>
            <p>Bibliographic citation is an essential and required element for every entry in
                <title>TSG</title>.</p>
            <p>The intellectual contribution and purpose of <title>TSG</title> is to establish URIs
              to compile and connect data from previous scholarship on the topic of Syriac Studies.
              Accordingly, our editorial policy assumes that our records will be primarily composed
              of information cited from primary and secondary sources. As a reference work,
                <title>TSG</title> is not intended as a venue for the first publication of original
              research. In general, our default editorial position will be to accept scholarly
              consensus and the results of existing scholarship as published. It is not within the
              scope of <title>TSG</title> to systematically review and correct past scholarship in
              the field. Nevertheless, authors of <title>TSG</title> records should not knowingly
              reproduce errors in previous scholarship. In the rare cases in which they are needed,
              encoding conventions for marking <foreign>incerta</foreign>, <foreign>errata</foreign>
              and <foreign>corrigenda</foreign> with regard to past scholarship are discussed below;
              see <ref target="#certainty">Certainty</ref>.</p>
            <div xml:id="purposeWorksCited">
              <head>Function of <q>Works Cited</q></head>
              <p>Each <title>TSG</title> record must include a list of <q>Works Cited</q> at the end
                of the record. This bibliographic list will be visually presented as numbered
                footnotes on the record webpage and labelled as <q>Works Cited</q>. This list is
                  <emph>NOT</emph> intended to be a general bibliography related to the place
                described and thus should only include works actually cited in the record. (The
                editorial work of gathering and classifying a general bibliography related to
                specific places falls within the scope of <ref
                  target="https://syriaca.org/cbss/index.html"><title>The Comprehensive Bibliography
                    on Syriac Studies</title></ref> rather than <title>TSG</title>).</p>
              <p>A technical discussion of how to encode bibliographic items into the <q>Works
                  Cited</q> section is given below, see <ref target="#bibl"><q>Works Cited</q>
                    (<gi>bibl</gi>)</ref>.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div xml:id="TEIcustomization">
            <head>Customization of the TEI Guidelines</head>
            <p>When considering the TEI XML schema created for <title>TSG</title>, it is essential
              to note that we have customized these guidelines specifically for use in digitally
              encoding geographic data related to the field of Syriac studies. Due to this
              specialized use, these guidelines do not include all possible TEI XML features which
              might be employed for history or geography data in general. Moreover, because the main
              language of <title>TSG</title> is English, these guidelines assume that each file will
              designate English as its main language.</p>
            <p>We have written the guidelines below with the assumption that the resulting XML files
              for the <ref target="https://syriaca.org/geo"><title>The Syriac
                Gazetteer</title></ref> will be displayed using the custom <title>Gaddel App</title>
              developed by Syriaca.org and The Digital Lab at Vanderbilt University. We have also
              made an effort to ensure (as much as possible) that our data will be easily serialized
              to conform to the data model developed by the <ref target="https://pleiades.stoa.org/"
                  ><title>Pleiades</title></ref> project, a community-built gazetteer for the field
              of ancient studies, and to the <ref target="https://pelagios.org/"><title>Pelagios
                  Network</title>'s</ref> implementation of Linked Open Data principles.</p>
            <p>For a more detailed discussion of the data model and architecture of Syriaca.org,
              readers are encouraged to consult the following technical publication: David A.
              Michelson, “Using Linked Open Data to Model Cultural Heritage Information: The
              Research Questions and Data Structures of the Syriaca.org Knowledge Graph,” in
                <title>Linked Open Data for the Ancient Mediterranean: Structures, Practices,
                Prospects</title>, edited by Sarah E. Bond, Paul Dilley, and Ryan Horne, <title>ISAW
                Papers</title> 20 (2021), <ref target="http://hdl.handle.net/2333.1/69p8d8cc"
                >http://hdl.handle.net/2333.1/69p8d8cc</ref>. </p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div xml:id="conventions">
          <head>Syriaca.org Encoding Conventions (Applies to Multiple Elements)</head>
          <p>This section describes encoding conventions which can be employed with a
            number of different elements. In particular these conventions are used with the
            following elements, unless otherwise specified: <gi>desc</gi>, <gi>event</gi>, <gi>location</gi>, 
            <gi>placeName</gi>, <gi>quote</gi>, <gi>relation</gi>, and <gi>state</gi>.</p>
          <div xml:id="languageCodes">
            <head>Recording Language Information (<att>xml:lang</att>)</head>
            <p>The language of an element's textual contents, such as that of a name variant,
               should be explicitly recorded using an <att>xml:lang</att> attribute. The
              contents of this attribute should be an <ref target="https://www.iso.org/iso-639-language-code">ISO 639 Language code</ref>.
              Syriaca.org employs the two-character ISO 639-1 codes where possible, e.g. <q>en</q>
              rather than <q>eng</q>. If no two-character code is available, use a three-character
              code from ISO 639-2 or ISO639-3. For textual contents in the Syriac language, Syriaca's
              convention is to use <q>syr</q> rather than <q>syc</q> to avoid confusion over distinguishing
              "Classical Syriac". For more on language code usage, see <ref target="https://syriaca.org/documentation/isostandards.html">Syriaca.org Documentation: Language and Script Identifiers</ref>.
              </p>
              <p>Explict tagging of language codes using <att>xml:lang</att> attributes is required 
                 on the following elements: <gi>placeName</gi>, <gi>desc</gi>, and <gi>note</gi>
                as in the following examples:
              <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                <placeName xml:lang="syr" xml:id="name78-13" source="#bib78-14">ܡܕܝܢܬܐ</placeName>
                <desc xml:lang="en">
                  <quote source="#bib78-1">183. Edessa</quote>
                </desc>
                <note xml:lang="en" type="incerta" resp="http://syriaca.org">GEDSH article identifies its river as the Balikh, but the identification is contested.</note>
              </egXML></p>
            <p>Finally, in some instances a <gi>desc</gi> or <gi>note</gi> element may contain content
              in multiple languages, such as an English description that includes a Syriac place name that
              is transcribed, rather than transliterated. In such cases, the language of the majority of the textual
              contents should be used as the <att>xml:lang</att> of the containing element. The portions of text in 
              a different language should be tagged with a <gi>foreign</gi> element, indicating that its contents are
              in a <q>foreign</q> language <emph>from the perspective of the containing element</emph>. The <gi>foreign</gi>
              element should have its own <att>xml:lang</att> attribute whose contents are the ISO 639 langauge code
              corresponding to the language of its contents, as seen in the following example:
              <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                <desc xml:lang="en">Attestation of name <foreign xml:lang="syr">ܐܘܿܪܫܠܹܡ</foreign> in a note in <title>Jerusalem, Saint Mark's Monastery, Ms. 181 [HMML SMMJ 00181]</title>.</desc>
              </egXML>
              This use of the <gi>foreign</gi> element, moreover, enables the HTML view to more precisely display
              content with bidirectional text (i.e., a mixture of right-to-left and left-to-right writing systems).
            </p>
          </div>
          <div xml:id="dates">
            <head>Recording Date Information for Occurrences and Durations</head>
            <p>In certain cases, contributors may wish to provide information about the
               temporal limits of a particular piece of information about a place. For example,
               the duration of a given settlement's existence, or the date on which a historical 
               event occurred. Date information for these cases is provided by one or more of the
               following attributes: <att>when</att>, <att>from</att>, <att>to</att>, <att>notBefore</att>,
               and <att>notAfter</att>. These attributes can be used to qualify a <gi>event</gi> or <gi>state</gi>
               element with temporal information. To record a date for an event that occurred at a particular
               point in time, use the <att>when</att> attribute:
            <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
              <event type="other" when="0201" source="#bib78-1">
                <desc xml:lang="en">Flood of the river <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/191">Daiṣan</placeName> destroyed part of city.</desc>
              </event>
            </egXML>
            Durations in time, on the other hand, must use either a <att>from</att>/<att>to</att> or
            <att>notBefore</att>/<att>notAfter</att> attribute pair depending on the certainty of the date range.
              The use of <att>from</att>/<att>to</att> attributes represents a date range with a high degree of certainty, 
              whereas uncertain or approximate date ranges should  be expressed with <att>notBefore</att>/<att>notAfter</att> attributes.
              The latter is more common for historical events, so is the preferred method.
            <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
              <event type="other" notBefore="1913" notAfter="1919" source="#bib78-1">
                <desc xml:lang="en">Massacres of some of Armenian and Syriac Christians during World War I.</desc>
              </event>
            </egXML>
            </p>
            <p>The values of these temporal attributes must be expressed as a date following the 
              <ref target="https://www.iso.org/iso-8601-date-and-time-format.html">ISO 8601 Date and Time format</ref>,
              that is <code>YYYY-MM-DD</code>, i.e. the year followed by month followed by day. In most cases, however, only
              the year can or should be included, e.g. <q>1014</q>. For dates prior to the year 1000, leading zeroes must be
              supplied to ensure a four-digit year, e.g. <q>0751</q>, <q>0010</q>, <q>0004</q>. Positive year values express
              dates in the Common Era (CE); for earlier dates, use a negative year value: <q>-0450</q> corresponds to 450 BCE
              (this practice corresponds to the W3C standard <ref target="https://www.w3.org/TR/xmlschema-2/#dateTime"> XML Schema Part 2: Datatypes Second Edition</ref>.</p>
            <p>For more information on the use of dates within Syriaca.org, including guidelines for approximating date ranges
              for imprecise or uncertain ranges, see the <ref target="https://github.com/srophe/syriaca-data/wiki/Dating-Conventions">Syriaca.org Dating Conventions</ref> document.</p>
            <div xml:id="datePrecision">
              <head>Recording Uncertainty for Event and Status Dates (<gi>precision</gi>)</head>
              <p>When recording date ranges for <ref target="#eventTypes">Events</ref> (<gi>event</gi>) or 
                <ref target="#statusTypes">Historical Status</ref> (<gi>state</gi>, e.g. existence dates)
                it may be necessary to further qualify the (un)certainty of the attributes used to record the date range. 
                For example, the Monastery of Rabban Hormizd (URI: <ref target="http://syriaca.org/place/168">http://syriaca.org/place/168</ref>), near Alqosh, 
                was founded some time in the mid-7th century CE and abandoned in the late 18th century (before being re-founded in 1808). 
                Simply using <att>notBefore</att> and <att>notAfter</att> is insufficient in this case, since we cannot know 
                if the terminus dates refer to the uncertain start range or the uncertain end range.
                The <title>TSG</title> uses the <gi>precision</gi> element to more precisely express these date ranges. 
                For example, the Monastery of Rabban Hormizd's existence dates (prior to its re-founding in 1808), may be expressed as follows:
                <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                  <state resp="http://syriaca.org" type="existence" from="0650" to="1800">
                    <precision match="@from" notBefore="0600" notAfter="0700"/>
                    <precision match="@to" notBefore="1773"  notAfter="1800"/>
                  </state>
                </egXML>
                In the <gi>state</gi> element, the date range is expressed using <att>from</att> and <att>to</att>
                attributes. These attributes are each qualified using the <gi>precision</gi> elements,
                which have a <att>match</att> attribute whose value must be one of the date attributes
                on the parent element, and must be preceded by the <code>@</code> symbol to indicate
                that they are attributes. The <gi>precision</gi> element then qualifies of the value
                of the targeted attribute using <att>notBefore</att> and/or <att>notAfter</att> attributes.
                In the above example, the founding date is qualified to be <q>sometime between 600 and 700 CE</q>
                and the abandonment date <q>sometime between 1773 and 1800 CE</q>.</p>
                <p>The <gi>precision</gi> element can also be used, more simply, to indicate that a date
                  attribute expresses an uncertain, rather than precise, terminus ante, or post, quem, as
                  in the following example:
                  <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                    <state resp="http://syriaca.org" type="existence" from="0525">
                      <precision match="@from" notAfter="0525"/>
                    </state>
                  </egXML>
                  Here, the <gi>precision</gi> element indicates that this places existence began no later
                  than 525 CE, but may have begun prior to this date.
              </p>
              <p>Technical Note: This use of the <gi>precision</gi> element was added to the TEI
                guidelines by the TEI consortium at the request of Syriaca.org for the specific
                use cases described above. Additional documentation can be found (as of 2018) at
                <ref target="https://sourceforge.net/p/tei/feature-requests/519/">TEI Feature
                  Request [#519]</ref> and <ref
                    target="https://listserv.brown.edu/archives/cgi-bin/wa?A2=tei-l;fc2bf4f.1307"
                    >The TEI Discussion List</ref>. </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div xml:id="attribution">
            <head>Sources and Attribution of Intellectual Credit</head>
            <p>When encoding child elements nested within <gi>place</gi>, <title>TSG</title> records
              are required to cite their sources using either the <att>source</att> or
                <att>resp</att> attributes. These attributes can be placed on any of these elements:
              <gi>desc</gi>, <gi>event</gi>, <gi>location</gi>, 
              <gi>placeName</gi>, <gi>quote</gi>, <gi>relation</gi>, and <gi>state</gi>.
            </p>
            <p>Whenever possible, the editorial policy of <title>TSG</title> is that all information
              in a record should have citations to bibliographic references found in the <q>Works
                Cited</q> section of the record. Citations should be made using <att>source</att> as
              described below in <ref target="#source">Inserting Bibliographic Citations
                  (<att>source</att>)</ref>. In rare cases, editors of <title>TSG</title> may
              provide attribution information not sourced to a primary or secondary source using the
                <att>resp</att> attribute as described below; see <ref target="resp">Asserting
                Information without a Source (<att>resp</att>)</ref>. The use of <att>source</att>
              and <att>resp</att> are mutually exclusive. Editors should use <att>resp</att> only
              when it is not possible to use <att>source</att>.</p>
            <div xml:id="source">
              <head>Inserting Bibliographic Citations (<att>source</att>)</head>
              <p>Use of the <att>source</att> attribute is a method for pointing to a bibliographic
                item found in the <q>Works Cited</q> section of the XML document. Before using
                  <att>source</att>, editors must first encode an entry for the bibliographic item
                using the <gi>bibl</gi> element and a assign it an ID as described in the
                documentation section <ref target="#bibl"><q>Works Cited</q>
                (<gi>bibl</gi>)</ref>.</p>
              <p>Once a <gi>bibl</gi> element for the item has been created, citations to that same
                bibliographic item can be inserted (and repeated) almost anywhere in the place
                record. These citations are inserted using the <att>source</att> attribute which is
                permitted on the following elements: <gi>desc</gi>, <gi>event</gi>, <gi>location</gi>, 
                <gi>placeName</gi>, <gi>quote</gi>, <gi>relation</gi>, and <gi>state</gi>.
                For example, the source of a place name would be indicated by a <att>source</att>
                attribute of the <gi>placeName</gi> element. Here is a specific example for the
                place of Edessa (URI <ref target="https://syriaca.org/place/78"
                  >https://syriaca.org/place/78</ref>) which has the modern name "Urfa": <egXML
                  xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                  <place>
                    <placeName source="#bib78-1">Urfa</placeName>
                    <desc>...</desc>
                    <bibl xml:id="bib78-1">
                      <ptr target="http://syriaca.org/cbss/C5T777C3"/>
                      <citedRange unit="p">138-139</citedRange>
                    </bibl>
                  </place>
                </egXML> In this example, Edessa’s modern name <q>Urfa</q> is given on the authority
                of an article in <ref target="http://syriaca.org/cbss/C5T777C3"
                  ><title>GEDSH</title></ref>. The citation is made by linking the
                  <gi>placeName</gi> and <gi>bibl</gi> elements by use of the bibl's xml:id
                  <code>"bib78-1"</code> supplied as an anchor (i.e., prefixed with a
                <code>#</code>) in a <att>source</att> attribute on the <gi>placeName</gi> element:
                  <code>source="#bib78-1"</code>.</p>
              <p>It is also possible to cite multiple sources for the same element. In these cases,
                the value of the <att>source</att> attribute is the xml:id for each source, with a
                prefixed <code>#</code>, and delimited by spaces. For example, the name
                  <q>Edessa</q> is attested in multiple separate sources, so that fact can be
                encoded as follows <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                  <placeName xml:id="name78-1" source="#bib78-1 #bib78-2 #bib78-6 #bib78-23"
                    >Edessa</placeName>
                </egXML> The addition of multiple citations for the same piece of information is, in
                general, not necessary or even recommended. When it occurs in <title>TSG</title> it
                is often the result of the bulk importing of data. As an editorial practice for
                individual authors, a single source is all that is required (and recommended) for
                most information. When multiple sources are listed in a single <att>source</att>
                attribute, they should be sorted in ascending order based on the second numeric
                value in the xml:id, as demonstrated in the example above (-1, -2, -6, -23, etc.).
              </p>
            </div>
            <div xml:id="quote">
              <head>Indicating Direct Quotations</head>
              <p>Direct quotations are indicated in <title>TSG</title> according to two different
                methods: transcription using <gi>placeName</gi> and quotation using
                <gi>quote</gi>.</p>
              <div>
                <head>Transcribing Place Names (<gi>placeName</gi>)</head>
                <p>Transcriptions of name variants should be collected and encoded in
                    <gi>placeName</gi> elements as a direct child of the <gi>place</gi> element.
                  These <gi>placeName</gi> elements must include a citation (using
                  <att>source</att>) and their contents are be defintion interpreted to be verbatim
                  quotations, with no further markup needed. See the discussion above concerning
                    <ref target="#source">Inserting Bibliographic Citations
                  (<att>source</att>)</ref>. For more on supplying name variants in <title>TSG</title>
                  entries, see below under <ref target="#placeName">Place Names (<gi>placeName</gi>)</ref></p>
              </div>
              <div>
                <head>Reporting Direct Quotations (<gi>quote</gi>)</head>
                <p>In all other instances, direct quotations should be encoded by use of the
                    <gi>quote</gi> element. The opening and closing of the <gi>quote</gi> element
                  should mark the start and conclusion of the quotation. There is no need to use
                  quotation marks in addition to the <gi>quote</gi> element. Quotation marks will be
                  auto-generated and added to the HTML view of the record. All <gi>quote</gi>
                  elements must include a citation (using <att>source</att>) following the method
                  described above concerning <ref target="#source">Inserting Bibliographic Citations
                      (<att>source</att>)</ref>.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div xml:id="resp">
              <head>Asserting Information without a Source (<att>resp</att>)</head>
              <p>In rare cases, editors of <title>TSG</title> supply information not sourced to a
                primary or secondary source. To ensure that even this information is attributable to
                a source, elements that should be sourced but are otherwise lacking a <att>source</att> attribute should receive a
                  <att>resp</att> attribute with the value <q>http://syriaca.org</q> to indicate
                that the editors of the <title>TSG</title> are responsible for the inclusion of the
                information: <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                  <desc type="abstract" xml:lang="en" resp="http://syriaca.org">A city of <placeName
                      ref="http://syriaca.org/place/124">Mesopotamia</placeName>, the capital of the
                    ancient kingdom of <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/145"
                      >Osrhoene</placeName>, modern Urfa.</desc>
                </egXML> In the preceding example, a concise description of Edessa was composed by a
                contributor to the place record, indicated by the use of the <att>resp</att>
                attribute in place of a <att>source</att> attribute. </p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div xml:id="syriacaURIs">
            <head>Linking Persons, Places, Works, and Bibliography to Syriaca.org URIs</head>
            <p>As discussed above in the section <ref target="#syriacaDataModel">The Seven Core
                Entities of the Syriaca.org Data Model</ref>, one of the distinctive features of
                <title>TSG</title> is its integration with the <ref
                target="https://syriaca.org/index.html">Syriaca.org</ref> knowledge graph through
              the use of URIs to identify and link persons, places, literary works, and
              bibliography. For each of these entity types, Syriaca.org has published an
                <q>authority file</q> which assigns a URI or Uniform Resource Identifier to every
              unique entry. Besides <title>TSG</title> (the geography authority file), these
              authority files include <ref target="https://syriaca.org/persons/index.html"
                  ><title>The Syriac Biographical Dictionary</title></ref>, <ref
                target="https://syriaca.org/nhsl/index.html"><title>The New Handbook of Syriac
                  Literature</title></ref>, and the <ref
                target="https://syriaca.org/cbss/index.html"><title>Comprehensive Bibliography on
                  Syriac Studies</title></ref>.</p>
            <p>In the <title>TSG</title>, it is possible to link to Syriaca.org URIs within the
              following descriptive elements: <gi>desc</gi>, <gi>quote</gi>, or <gi>note</gi>. Use
              of Syriaca.org URIs to identify prose allusions to persons, places, works, etc. is
              strongly encouraged whenever possible. It should be noted that the use of Syriaca.org
              URIs in these sections is for descriptive purposes (i.e. relating the subject of the
                <title>TSG</title> record to other places, persons, etc.). The inclusion of URIs in
              these cases does <emph>NOT</emph> assign a URI to the place record. For that separate
              function, see the section below: <ref target="#idno">Identifiers
              (<gi>indo</gi>)</ref>.</p>
            <p>In all of the below cases, care should be taken with the placement of whitespace in the elements.
               When marking a string of text as a personal name, place name, work title, or bibliographic item,
               The opening and closing element tags must avoid leading and trailing whitespace. Whitespace must instead
               be placed outside of the element:
              <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                <desc><desc type="abstract" xml:lang="en" resp="http://syriaca.org"
                  corresp="http://syriaca.org/geo">A location with a monastery whose inhabitants
                  received a letter from <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/51">Severus of
                    Antioch</persName>.</desc></desc>
              </egXML>
              Notice, in the above example, that the space between "from " and the opening tag of the <gi>persName</gi> element,
              the lack of space between the opening tag and "Severus", no space between "Antioch" and the closing tag. No space is
              included following the closing tag since the sentence ends with a period; otherwise, a space would be expected before the next
              word in the sentence.
            </p>
            <div xml:id="allusionsPersons">
              <head>Allusions to Persons (<gi>persName</gi>/<att>ref</att>)</head>
              <p>References to persons can appear in <gi>desc</gi>, <gi>quote</gi>, or <gi>note</gi>
                elements (including when these are children of <gi>location</gi>, <gi>event</gi>,
                  <gi>state</gi>). In these cases, these persons should be linked to Syriaca.org
                URIs.</p>
              <p>When a <title>TSG</title> record refers to a person who has a Syriaca.org URI, the
                mention of a personal name should be tagged using the <gi>persName</gi> element and
                linked to the URI using <att>ref</att>. The Syriaca.org person URI should be first
                confirmed as valid in the <ref target="https://syriaca.org/persons/index.html"
                    ><title>Syriac Biographical Dictionary</title></ref>. In the following example,
                the place Tagai (<ref target="http://syriaca.org/place/1475"
                    ><code>http://syriaca.org/place/1475</code></ref>) is identified based on its
                relationship to a person: <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                  <desc type="abstract" xml:lang="en" resp="http://syriaca.org"
                    corresp="http://syriaca.org/geo">A location with a monastery whose inhabitants
                    received a letter from <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/51">Severus of
                      Antioch</persName>.</desc>
                </egXML></p>
              <p>Because the URI and not the personal name serves as the identifier, it is not
                necessary to use a <q>preferred form</q> of the personal name. If the allusion is a
                quotation, the encoder should leave the wording as found in the original.</p>
              <p>Person URIs should be attached only to direct references to persons. When a
                personal name occurs as part of a title of a work (e.g. <title>The Homilies of John
                  Chrysostom</title>) or as part of a place name (e.g. The Convent of Mar Isaac),
                these entities should be treated as works or places respectively. In these cases the
                prose is marked with a <gi>title</gi> or <gi>placeName</gi> element instead and the
                personal name must not be tagged nor person URIs attached.</p>
            </div>
            <div xml:id="allusionsPlaces">
              <head>Allusions to Places (<gi>placeName</gi>/<att>ref</att>)</head>
              <p>References to places can appear in <gi>desc</gi>, <gi>quote</gi>, or <gi>note</gi>
                elements (including when these are children of <gi>location</gi>, <gi>event</gi>,
                  <gi>state</gi>). In these cases, these places should be linked to Syriaca.org
                URIs.</p>
              <p>When descriptive prose in a <title>TSG</title> record refers to a place that has a
                Syriaca.org URI, the mention of the place should be tagged using the
                  <gi>placeName</gi> element and linked to a URI.</p>
              <p><emph>Nota Bene</emph>: The <gi>placeName</gi> element is used in two ways in
                  <title>TSG</title>. This present section refers only to the secondary use of
                  <gi>placeName</gi> elements in marking up prose descriptions in <title>TSG</title>
                with URIs. The primary use of the <gi>placeName</gi> element is to collate place
                name variants related to a <title>TSG</title> entry. For the name variant use case
                of <gi>placeName</gi> please see the <ref target="#placeName">Place Names
                    (<gi>placeName</gi>)</ref> section below.</p>
              <p>All <gi>placeName</gi> elements used in this secondary, descriptive usage are
                required to have a <att>ref</att> attribute which points to a Syriaca.org place URI.
                In the following example, the settlement Gazarta (<ref
                  target="http://syriaca.org/place/88"
                  ><code>http://syriaca.org/place/88</code></ref>) is identified based on its
                relationship to three other places:<egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                  <desc type="abstract" xml:lang="en" resp="http://syriaca.org"
                    corresp="http://syriaca.org/geo">A city on the <placeName
                      ref="http://syriaca.org/place/202">Tigris river</placeName> between <placeName
                      ref="http://syriaca.org/place/8">Amida</placeName> and <placeName
                      ref="http://syriaca.org/place/139">Mosul</placeName>.</desc>
                </egXML>
              </p>
              <p>Places URIs should be attached only to direct references to places. When a personal
                name occurs as part of a title of a work (e.g. <title>The Chronicle of
                  Edessa</title>) or as part of a personal name (e.g. Jacob of Edessa), these
                entities should be treated as works or persons respectively. In these cases the
                prose is marked with a <gi>title</gi> or <gi>persName</gi> instead and the
                geographic epithet must not be tagged nor place URIs attached.</p>
            </div>
            <div xml:id="allusionsWorks">
              <head>Allusions to Literary Works (<gi>title</gi>/<att>ref</att>)</head>
              <p>References to texts or literary works can appear in <gi>desc</gi>, <gi>quote</gi>,
                or <gi>note</gi> elements (including when these are children of <gi>location</gi>,
                  <gi>event</gi>, <gi>state</gi>). In these cases, these works should be linked to
                Syriaca.org URIs.</p>
              <p>When a <title>TSG</title> record refers to a literary work that has a Syriaca.org
                URI, the title or mention of the work should be tagged using the <gi>title</gi>
                element and linked to the URI using the <att>ref</att> attribute.</p>
              <p><emph>Nota Bene</emph>: At present Syriaca.org's authority file for literary works
                is incomplete, so not all works may have available URIs.</p>
              <p>In the following example, the church of Mar Thomas the Apostle (<ref
                  target="http://syriaca.org/place/2593"
                  ><code>http://syriaca.org/place/2593</code></ref>) is identified based on its
                relationship to a primary source. relationship to three other places: <egXML
                  xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                  <desc type="abstract" xml:lang="en" source="#bib2593-1 #bib2593-2"
                    corresp="http://syriaca.org/geo">A church in Edessa where the coffin of
                      <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/2123">Thomas the Apostle</persName>
                    was placed, according to a tradition recorded in the <title
                      ref="http://syriaca.org/work/8559">Chronicle of Edessa</title>. </desc>
                </egXML>
              </p>
              <p>Work URIs should be attached only to direct references to works. When the title of
                a work occurs as part of a personal name (e.g. Author of <title>The Macarian
                  Homilies</title>) or in a yet unidentified case where a work title might occur as
                part of a place name, these entities should be treated as persons or places
                respectively. In these cases the prose is marked with a <gi>persName</gi> or a
                  <gi>placeName</gi> instead and the work title must not be tagged nor work URIs
                attached. It is also useful to distinguish between a <q>work</q> and a
                  <q>bibliographic item</q>. The former is an abstract concept (<title>The Chronicle
                  of Edessa</title>, URI: <ref target="http://syriaca.org/work/8559"
                    ><code>http://syriaca.org/work/8559</code></ref>), while a bibliographic item
                refers to a specific instance of a publication (e.g. Guidi's 1902 edition, URI: <ref
                  target="https://syriaca.org/cbss/63ZKDBEH"
                    ><code>http://syriaca.org/cbss/63ZKDBEH</code></ref>).</p>
            </div>
            <div xml:id="allusionsBibliographic">
              <head>Allusions to Bibliographic Items
                (<gi>bibl</gi>/<gi>ref</gi>/<att>target</att>) -- Planned Implementation</head>
              <p><emph>The encoding feature below has not yet been implemented but is planned for the future.</emph></p>
              <p>References to Bibliographic Items can appear in <gi>desc</gi>, <gi>quote</gi>, or
                  <gi>note</gi> elements (including when these are children of <gi>location</gi>,
                  <gi>event</gi>, <gi>state</gi>). In these cases, these items should be linked to
                Syriaca.org URIs.</p>
              <p><emph>Nota Bene</emph>: The <gi>bibl</gi> element is used in two ways in
                  <title>TSG</title>. This present section refers only to the secondary use of
                  <gi>bibl</gi> elements in marking up prose descriptions in <title>TSG</title> with
                URIs. The primary use of the <gi>bibl</gi> element is to create the individual
                entries for the <q>Works Cited</q> section for a <title>TSG</title> record. For the
                  <q>Works Cited</q> use case of the <gi>bibl</gi> element please see the <ref
                  target="#bibl"><q>Works Cited</q> (<gi>bibl</gi>)</ref> section below.</p>
              <p><emph>In addition: This feature is currently not implemented in TSG.</emph></p>
              <p>When the title of secondary biblographic items (books, articles, etc.) are
                mentioned, they can be tagged with the <gi>bibl</gi> element. The bibliographic item
                may be linked with a <title>CBSS</title> URI by using a child <gi>ref</gi> element
                with the URI placed in a <att>target</att> attribute of the <gi>ref</gi> element.
                Note the distinction here in the use of a <gi>ref</gi> element rather than a
                  <att>ref</att> attribute as used for linking URIs for persons, places, or literary
                works as described above.</p>
              <p>In the following example, a <gi>note</gi> on the settlement Ayn Dābā (<ref
                  target="http://syriaca.org/place/434"
                  ><code>http://syriaca.org/place/434</code></ref>) includes a scholarly discussion
                of a modern translation: 
                <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                  <note xml:lang="en" type="errata" resp="http://syriaca.org"><bibl><ref
                        target="http://syriaca.org/cbss/SGBVKKGH">Dolabani's Syriac
                        translation</ref></bibl> erroneously identifies this place with <placeName
                      ref="http://syriaca.org/place/9">Anazarba</placeName>.</note>
                </egXML></p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div xml:id="recordStructure">
          <head>Record Structure</head>
          <p>This section describes the TEI XML structure of each <title>NHSL</title> work record,
            following the order in which elements appear in the document.</p>

          <div xml:id="rootElement">
            <head>The TEI Root Element (<gi>TEI</gi>)</head>
            <p>Every <title>NHSL</title> record begins with the <gi>TEI</gi> root element, which
              must include the namespace declarations and an <att>xml:lang</att> attribute with the
              value <q>en</q>, reflecting that the primary language of record data is English:
              <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                <TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:srophe="https://srophe.app"
                  xml:lang="en">
                  <teiHeader>...</teiHeader>
                  <text>...</text>
                </TEI>
              </egXML>
            </p>
            <p>The <gi>TEI</gi> root element must always contain exactly two child elements:
              <gi>teiHeader</gi> and <gi>text</gi>.</p>
          </div>

          <div xml:id="header">
            <head>The TEI Header (<gi>teiHeader</gi>)</head>
            <p>The <gi>teiHeader</gi> element contains metadata about the record itself: who created
              it, what it describes, what license covers it, and what series it belongs to. The
              structure of the <gi>teiHeader</gi> in <title>NHSL</title> records is as follows:</p>
            <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
              <teiHeader>
                <fileDesc>
                  <titleStmt>...</titleStmt>
                  <editionStmt>...</editionStmt>
                  <publicationStmt>...</publicationStmt>
                  <seriesStmt>...</seriesStmt>
                  <sourceDesc>...</sourceDesc>
                </fileDesc>
                <encodingDesc>...</encodingDesc>
                <profileDesc>...</profileDesc>
                <revisionDesc>...</revisionDesc>
              </teiHeader>
            </egXML>

            <div xml:id="titleStmt">
              <head>Title Statement (<gi>titleStmt</gi>)</head>
              <p>The <gi>titleStmt</gi> records the title of the record (which mirrors the work's
                primary English headword title), the institutional sponsors and funders, and the
                editors and contributors. The <gi>title</gi> in the <gi>titleStmt</gi> gives both
                an English form and a Syriac form separated by an em dash, enclosed in a
                <gi>foreign</gi> element:</p>
              <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                <titleStmt>
                  <title level="a" xml:lang="en">Genesis (Peshitta version) — <foreign
                    xml:lang="syr">ܣܦܪܐ ܕܒܪܝܫܝܬ</foreign></title>
                  <sponsor>Syriaca.org: The Syriac Reference Portal</sponsor>
                  <funder>The National Endowment for the Humanities</funder>
                  <editor role="creator"
                    ref="http://syriaca.org/documentation/editors.xml#ngibson">Nathan P.
                    Gibson</editor>
                  <respStmt>
                    <resp>Editing, data entry, and reconciling by</resp>
                    <name ref="http://syriaca.org/documentation/editors.xml#ngibson">Nathan P.
                      Gibson</name>
                  </respStmt>
                </titleStmt>
              </egXML>
              <p>The <gi>editor</gi> element must carry a <att>role</att> attribute (either
                <q>creator</q> or <q>contributor</q>) and a <att>ref</att> attribute pointing to
                the Syriaca.org editor URI. Editor URIs take the form
                <code>http://syriaca.org/documentation/editors.xml#[initials]</code>. New
                contributors should contact the Syriaca editors to obtain an editor URI.</p>
            </div>

            <div xml:id="publicationStmt">
              <head>Publication Statement (<gi>publicationStmt</gi>)</head>
              <p>The <gi>publicationStmt</gi> records the publishing authority, the URI of this TEI
                file (formed by appending <code>/tei</code> to the work URI), the license, and the
                date the record was created:</p>
              <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                <publicationStmt>
                  <authority>Syriaca.org: The Syriac Reference Portal</authority>
                  <idno type="URI">http://syriaca.org/work/1/tei</idno>
                  <availability>
                    <licence target="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/">
                      <p>Distributed under a Creative Commons Attribution 3.0 Unported License.</p>
                    </licence>
                  </availability>
                  <date>2017-03-23+01:00</date>
                </publicationStmt>
              </egXML>
              <p>When a record incorporates data from a third-party source under a specific license
                (such as the <title>Bibliotheca Hagiographica Syriaca</title>), an additional
                <gi>p</gi> element within <gi>licence</gi> notes the copyrighted material and its
                license terms.</p>
            </div>

            <div xml:id="seriesStmt">
              <head>Series Statements (<gi>seriesStmt</gi>)</head>
              <p>Each <title>NHSL</title> record belongs to the overarching series and to one or
                more sub-series. Each membership is recorded in a separate <gi>seriesStmt</gi>
                element. Every record must include at minimum the top-level <title>NHSL</title>
                series statement. Additional <gi>seriesStmt</gi> elements record membership in
                thematic sub-series such as <title>A Guide to the Bible in Syriac</title> or the
                <title>Bibliotheca Hagiographica Syriaca Electronica</title>:</p>
              <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                <seriesStmt>
                  <title level="s" xml:lang="en">A New Handbook of Syriac Literature</title>
                  <editor role="general"
                    ref="http://syriaca.org/documentation/editors.xml#ngibson">Nathan P.
                    Gibson</editor>
                  <editor role="general"
                    ref="http://syriaca.org/documentation/editors.xml#dmichelson">David A.
                    Michelson</editor>
                  <idno type="URI">http://syriaca.org/nhsl</idno>
                </seriesStmt>
                <seriesStmt>
                  <title level="m" xml:lang="en">A Guide to the Bible in Syriac</title>
                  <editor role="general"
                    ref="http://syriaca.org/documentation/editors.xml#ngibson">Nathan P.
                    Gibson</editor>
                  <editor role="general"
                    ref="http://syriaca.org/documentation/editors.xml#dmichelson">David A.
                    Michelson</editor>
                  <biblScope unit="vol" n="2"/>
                  <idno type="URI">http://syriaca.org/bible</idno>
                </seriesStmt>
              </egXML>
            </div>

            <div xml:id="revisionDesc">
              <head>Record Change Log (<gi>revisionDesc</gi>)</head>
              <p>The <gi>revisionDesc</gi> element records the editorial history of the record. It
                must carry a <att>status</att> attribute indicating the current state of the record.
                Permitted values include <q>draft</q>, <q>uncorrected-draft</q>, and
                <q>published</q>. Within <gi>revisionDesc</gi>, each editorial action is recorded in
                a <gi>change</gi> element, listed in reverse chronological order (most recent
                first). Each <gi>change</gi> element must have <att>who</att> (the editor URI of the
                person making the change) and <att>when</att> (an ISO 8601 datetime) attributes.
                The text of the <gi>change</gi> element should begin with one of the following
                terms: <q>CREATED</q> (used only for the initial creation of the record),
                <q>ADDED</q>, or <q>CHANGED</q>:</p>
              <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                <revisionDesc status="uncorrected-draft">
                  <change who="http://syriaca.org/documentation/editors.xml#ngibson"
                    when="2017-03-27+02:00">CHANGED: Merged in data from duplicate record.</change>
                  <change who="http://syriaca.org/documentation/editors.xml#ngibson" n="1.0"
                    when="2017-03-23+01:00">CREATED: work</change>
                </revisionDesc>
              </egXML>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div xml:id="bodyStructure">
            <head>The Body Structure (<gi>text</gi> and <gi>body</gi>)</head>
            <p>The intellectual content of each <title>NHSL</title> record is contained in the
              <gi>text</gi> element, which holds a <gi>body</gi> element containing a single
              <gi>bibl</gi> element. The XPath to the main data element is therefore
              <code>/TEI/text/body/bibl</code>. The overall structure is as follows:</p>
            <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
              <text>
                <body>
                  <bibl xml:id="work-1" type="lawd:ConceptualWork" ana="#syriaca-biblical">
                    <!-- titles, author, identifiers, notes, relations, bibliography -->
                  </bibl>
                </body>
              </text>
            </egXML>
          </div>

          <div xml:id="biblElement">
            <head>Description of the Literary Work (<gi>bibl</gi>)</head>
            <p>The primary container for all data about a literary work is the <gi>bibl</gi>
              element. This usage adapts the TEI <gi>bibl</gi> element — normally used for
              bibliographic references — to serve as the top-level container for work descriptions.
              This choice reflects the strongly bibliographic character of <title>NHSL</title>
              records, which describe works primarily in terms of their editions, manuscripts, and
              scholarly literature, rather than providing discursive prose descriptions.</p>
            <p>The <gi>bibl</gi> element must carry an <att>xml:id</att> attribute of the form
              <code>work-[n]</code> (where <code>[n]</code> is the numeric portion of the work URI)
              and must carry <att>type</att> and <att>ana</att> attributes (see <ref
                target="#biblType">Work Types</ref> below). The <gi>bibl</gi> element can contain
              the following child elements in the order listed, some of which are required:</p>
            <list>
              <item><gi>title</gi>* — one or more work title variants (see <ref
                  target="#title">Titles</ref>)</item>
              <item><gi>author</gi> or <gi>editor</gi>— the work's attributed creator(s) (see <ref
                  target="#creator">Creators</ref>)</item>
              <item><gi>idno</gi>* — one or more identifiers, including the canonical Syriaca.org
                URI (see <ref target="#idno">Identifiers</ref>)</item>
              <item><gi>textLang</gi> — the primary language of the work (see <ref
                  target="#textLang">Text Language</ref>)</item>
              <item><gi>noteGrp</gi> — groups of notes recording incipits, explicits, and prologues
                (see <ref target="#noteGrp">Incipits, Explicits, and Prologues</ref>)</item>
              <item><gi>listRelation</gi> — relationships to other works, persons, or entities (see
                <ref target="#listRelation">Relations</ref>)</item>
              <item><gi>listBibl</gi>* — bibliographic information grouped by type (editions,
                manuscripts, translations, secondary literature) (see <ref
                  target="#listBibl">Bibliography</ref>)</item>
            </list>

            <div xml:id="biblType">
              <head>Work Types (<att>type</att> and <att>ana</att>)</head>
              <p>The <gi>bibl</gi> element must carry two classificatory attributes: <att>type</att>
                and <att>ana</att>. Together these attributes identify the ontological category of
                the work and its thematic classification within <title>NHSL</title>.</p>

              <div xml:id="typeAttr">
                <head>Ontological Type (<att>type</att>)</head>
                <p>The <att>type</att> attribute on <gi>bibl</gi> distinguishes between the two
                  fundamental kinds of work record used in <title>NHSL</title>. Its value must be
                  one of the following:</p>
                <list>
                  <item><code>lawd:ConceptualWork</code> — used for a specific textual work,
                    recension, or version that can be identified by concrete textual and material
                    evidence (incipits, manuscripts, editions, etc.). This is the most common type
                    and covers the majority of <title>NHSL</title> records. Example: the Peshitta
                    version of Genesis (<ref target="http://syriaca.org/work/1"
                      ><code>http://syriaca.org/work/1</code></ref>).</item>
                  <item><code>syriaca:LiteraryTradition</code> — used for a broader literary
                    tradition that encompasses multiple versions, translations, or adaptations of
                    the same underlying work. LiteraryTradition records generally do not carry
                    incipits or explicits and do not reference specific manuscripts. They serve
                    primarily as organizing nodes in the knowledge graph, linking specific
                    conceptual works to a common tradition. Example: the Genesis literary tradition
                    (<ref target="http://syriaca.org/work/9628"
                      ><code>http://syriaca.org/work/9628</code></ref>).</item>
                </list>
                <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                  <!-- A specific textual work: -->
                  <bibl xml:id="work-1" type="lawd:ConceptualWork" ana="#syriaca-biblical">...</bibl>

                  <!-- A broader literary tradition: -->
                  <bibl xml:id="work-9628" type="syriaca:LiteraryTradition" ana="#syriaca-biblical">...</bibl>
                </egXML>
              </div>

              <div xml:id="anaAttr">
                <head>Thematic Classification (<att>ana</att>)</head>
                <p>The <att>ana</att> attribute on <gi>bibl</gi> supplies a thematic classification
                  for the work using a Syriaca.org taxonomy term. Its value is a hashtag-prefixed
                  token that corresponds to one of the category identifiers defined in the
                  <gi>classDecl</gi>/<gi>taxonomy</gi> section of the <gi>encodingDesc</gi>.
                  Permitted values include:</p>
                <list>
                  <item><code>#syriaca-biblical</code> — the work is a version, commentary on, or
                    liturgical adaptation of a biblical text</item>
                  <item><code>#syriaca-hagiographic</code> — the work is a hagiographic text, such
                    as a saint's life, martyrdom account, or commemoration</item>
                </list>
                <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                  <bibl xml:id="work-567" ana="#syriaca-hagiographic">...</bibl>
                </egXML>
                <p>Note that <att>ana</att> is distinct from <att>type</att>: <att>type</att>
                  describes what <emph>kind</emph> of entity the record represents (conceptual work
                  vs. literary tradition), while <att>ana</att> describes its thematic
                  <emph>content</emph> (biblical, hagiographic, etc.).</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div xml:id="title">
            <head>Work Titles (<gi>title</gi>)</head>
            <p>Titles are essential for identifying and disambiguating individual literary works.
              Every record must include at least one <gi>title</gi> element, and may have any additional
              number of <gi>title</gi> elements. The text node of this element
              should contain a title by which the literary work is or was known.
              Name variants may be recorded for any language, and that language should be recorded as described
              in the <ref target="#languageCodes">Recording Language Information (<att>xml:lang</att>)</ref> section. 
              Each record must have at least one title in English or English transliteration indicated as the <ref target="#headword">headword</ref>.
              Multiple titles attested in manuscripts or in scholarly use may be collected, each recorded in their own
              <gi>title</gi> element.</p>
              <p>Additionally, <gi>title</gi> elements must have a unique <att>xml:id</att>
                attribute of the form <code>name\d+-\d+</code>. The first digits derive from the
                numerical portion of the Syriaca URI for the literary work, and the latter is a sequential
                integer: <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                  <title xml:id="name1-2" xml:lang="syr" srophe:tags="#syriaca-headword" source="#bib1-1">ܣܦܪܐ ܕܒܪܝܫܝܬ</title>
                </egXML> Finally, as seen in the preceding example, all <gi>title</gi> elements
                must indicate the source of the name form as detailed in the <ref target="#source">Inserting Citations</ref> section of these Guidelines. </p>

            <div xml:id="headwordTitles">
              <head>Syriaca Headwords</head>
              <p>At least one <gi>title</gi> element must be tagged as a Syriaca Headword
                  using a <att>srophe:tags</att> attribute with the value of
                    <q>#syriaca-headword</q>. As the headwords are used as preferred labels
                  and for alphabetization in search/browse results, at least one title in English or
                  English transliteration should be tagged as a headword. At most one headword per language may be defined.
                  <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                    <title xml:id="name3-1" xml:lang="en" srophe:tags="#syriaca-headword" resp="http://syriaca.org">Leviticus (Peshitta version)</title>
                    <title xml:id="name3-2" xml:lang="syr" srophe:tags="#syriaca-headword" source="#bib3-1 #bib3-2">ܣܦܪܐ ܕܟܗ̈ܢܐ</title>
                    <title xml:id="name3-3" xml:lang="en" source="#bib3-10 #bib3-20 #bib3-22 #bib3-24">Leviticus</title>
                  </egXML>
                </p>
              <!--
                From the Claude output, include?:
              <p>Headword titles for biblical works in <title>NHSL</title> are typically
                constructed by appending a parenthetical qualifier (e.g., <q>(Peshitta version)</q>,
                <q>(literary tradition)</q>) to the standard English title to ensure disambiguation.
                For hagiographic texts, the convention is to append <q>(text)</q> to distinguish
                the work record from a person record about the same saint.</p>
              -->
            </div>

            <div xml:id="titleTypes">
              <head>Title Types (<att>type</att>)</head>
              <p>Titles may be further classified using a <att>type</att> attribute. This practice is optional. Only the following
                values are permitted:</p>
              <list>
                <item><q>abbreviation</q>: a standard, abbreviated form of the work's title, such as those found in the SBL Handbook of Style. A
                  <att>srophe:tags</att> attribute with the value of <q>canonical</q> may mark abbreviations in widespread scholarly usage.
                  The abbreviation system should be cited as described in the 
                  <ref target="#source">Inserting Citations</ref> section of these Guidelines.</item>
                <item><q>supplied</q>: a title supplied by an editor or cataloger, often describing the
                  literary work in terms of its contents, rather than a title transcribed or
                  otherwise derived from a specific manuscript witness.</item>
                <item><q>type="final-rubric"</q>: the title as it appears in a subscription, or closing
                  rubric, of a specific manuscript witness.</item>
              </list>
              <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                <title xml:id="name1-4" xml:lang="en" type="abbreviation"
                  srophe:tags="#canonical" source="#bib1-9">Gen</title>
                <title xml:lang="en" type="supplied" xml:id="name1-6" source="#bib1-20">
                  The book of Genesis, according to the Peshitta version</title>
                <title xml:lang="syr" type="final-rubric" xml:id="name1-8" source="#bib1-32">
                  ܫܠܡ. ܣܦܪܐ. ܩܕܡܝܐ. ܒܪܝܬܐ</title>
              </egXML>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div xml:id="creator">
            <head>Creators (<gi>author</gi> and <gi>editor</gi>)</head>
            <p>Authors and other creators (translators, compilers, etc.) are recorded using
              <gi>author</gi> or <gi>editor</gi> elements, depending on the individual person's
              responsibility for the creation of the literary work. In both cases, the creator
              should have en entry in the <ref target="http://syriaca.org/persons"><title>Syriac Biographical Dictionary</title></ref>,
              and the Syriaca.org person URI should be included as the value of the <att>ref</att>
              attribute of the <gi>author</gi> or <gi>editor</gi> element. The contents of these
              elements, moreover, should be the text node of the person record's <code>/TEI/titleStmt/title</code> element:
              <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
              <author ref="http://syriaca.org/person/13" source="#bib567-1" xml:lang="en">
                Ephrem — <foreign xml:lang="syr">ܐܦܪܝܡ</foreign>
              </author>
            </egXML>
            As seen in the above example, the <gi>author</gi> or <gi>editor</gi> element for the creator
            should include an <att>xml:lang</att> attribute value of <q>en</q>.
          </p>
            <p>For creators other than authors, the <att>role</att> attribute must be used to further
            specify the peron's contribution. Allowed values include:
            <!-- TBD: add this list from the schema --></p>
          <p>Attribution of creators may also be included even in cases of dubious, disputed, or pseudopigraphic
            attribution. The <att>role</att> attribute may also be used for this purpose, in which case the
            following values should be used:
            <!--TBD: add this list from the schema -->

            <!--Proposed convention: include a note (what type?) explaining cases of uncertain or incorrect attribution -->
          </p>
          </div>

          <div xml:id="idno">
            <head>Identifiers (<gi>idno</gi>)</head>
            <p><emph>This element is required. A record must have at least one <gi>idno</gi>
                  indicating a Syriaca.org URI. Records belonging to more than one Syriaca.org
                  publication, must have an <gi>idno</gi> for each publication. A record may have
                  any number of additional <gi>idno</gi> elements.</emph></p>
            <p>As discussed above in the section on the <ref target="#concept">Concept of a
                  Work</ref>, URIs are an important part of delineating a literary work.
                  Each <title>NHSL</title> record must include one or more <gi>idno</gi> elements
              recording the unique identifiers associated with the work.
            The first of these <gi>idno</gi> elements must have the <att>type</att> attribute with
            a value of <q>URI</q>, and it must contain the Syriaca.org work URI for literary work
          which the record describes, of the form <code>http://syriaca.org/work/{\d+}</code>. Other <gi>idno</gi>
        elements with <att>type</att> attributes of <q>URI</q> may be included to connect the <title>NHSL</title>
      record with related concepts in other databases, such as <ref target="https://viaf.org"><title>Virtual International Authority File</title></ref>,
    or <ref target="https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Wikidata:Main_Page"><title>WikiData</title></ref>.
              <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                <idno type="URI">http://syriaca.org/work/1</idno>
                <idno type="URI">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Genesis</idno>
                <idno type="URI">https://www.wikidata.org/wiki/Q9184</idno>
                <idno type="URI">https://viaf.org/viaf/174582712</idno>
              </egXML>
          </p>
          <p>Less commonly, <gi>idno</gi> elements with <att>type</att> attribute values of <q>URN</q>, 
                referring to the <ref target="https://www.rfc-editor.org/info/rfc8141/">Uniform Resource Names</ref>
                URI scheme, may be included:
                <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                  <idno type="URN">urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0086.tlg028</idno>
                </egXML>
              </p>
            <div xml:id="referenceNumbers">
              <head>Standard Reference Numbers</head>
              <p>A work record may include additional <gi>idno</gi> elements identifying it
                according to standard schemas or in standard reference works. These <gi>idno</gi>
                elements must have a <att>type</att> attribute value of <q>number</q>. Their 
                <att>subtype</att> attribute specifies the reference work or identifier schema
                to which the refrence number belongs. The following sources are permitted:
                <!--Add with labels from the schema -->
              </p>
              <p>
                Example:
                <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                <idno type="number" subtype="BHS">347</idno>
                <idno type="number" subtype="BHO">870</idno>
              </egXML>
              </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div xml:id="textLang">
            <head>Text Language (<gi>textLang</gi>)</head>
            <p>The primary language of the work's text is recorded using a <gi>textLang</gi>
              element with a <att>mainLang</att> attribute whose value is an <ref target="https://www.iso.org/iso-639-language-code">ISO 639 Language code</ref>.
              See <ref target="#languageCodes">Recording Language Information (<att>xml:lang</att>)</ref>, above for more general
              information about using these language codes.
              For the overwhelming majority of <title>NHSL</title> records, the attribute value will be <q>syr</q>,
              for Syriac. This is the case even for literary works originally composed in languages other than Syriac, given the 
            linguistic scope of <title>NHSL</title>.</p>
            <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
              <textLang mainLang="syr"/>
            </egXML>
            <p>Only one <gi>textLang</gi> element is allowed. If a work is substantially bilingual or multilingual,
              additional languages may be recorded in the <att>otherLangs</att> attribute as a space-separated list 
              of ISO 639 Language codes.</p>
          </div>

          <div xml:id="noteGrp">
            <!--Generic header for noteGrps -->
            <head>Work Description, Notes, and Excerpts (<gi>noteGrp</gi>)</head>
            <p>Each work record contains one or more <gi>noteGrp</gi> elements that help to disambiguate
            this work from other similar works. These note groups include record abstracts; descriptive and discursive
          notes about the work; and excerpts from the work.</p>
          <p>The general structure of a <gi>noteGrp</gi> element is as follows. Each <gi>noteGrp</gi> element
             must have a <att>type</att> attribute and a child <gi>desc</gi> element. The <att>type</att> attribute's value 
             and the text node of the <gi>desc</gi> element must match those in the following table:
            <!--list these and describe? abstract, scope, versions, content, disambiguation, prologue, incipit, excerpt, explicit -->

            One or more child <gi>note</gi> elements may be included in a <gi>noteGrp</gi> element. These <gi>note</gi> elements must
            have a <att>type</att> attribute whose value corresponds to that of its parent <gi>noteGrp</gi> element. The language
            of the note must be recorded as described in <ref target="#languageCodes">Recording Language Information (<att>xml:lang</att>)</ref> above.
            The contents of the <gi>note</gi> element should be sourced  as
            described in the guidelines on <ref target="#source">Inserting Citations</ref>. If the contents are a direct quotation from the source,
            however, a child <gi>quote</gi> element should be included, and that element sourced per the above guidelines.
            <!-- example -->
            </p>
          <div xml:id="abstract">
            <head>Abstract</head>
            <p><emph>An English-language abstract is required. A record may have any number of
                  additional <gi>note</gi> elements.</emph></p> 
                  <p>Every record must have an abstract, i.e. a short description or one to two lines of
                prose describing the literary work. The purpose of the abstract is to help users of
                  <title>NHSL</title> to easily disambiguate search results and quickly identify the
                work for which they are searching. Abstracts should be written as complete sentences
                with proper punctuation. Ideally, an abstract should be at least one sentence in legnth
                 Every record must have an abstract written in English. It is also possible to add additional abstracts in
                other languages. Additionally, individual sub-volumes of <title>NHSL</title> may have
                their own, distinct abstracts.
                    <!-- Example-->
                Abstracts may be included in languages other than English, and each abstract
                must have its language recorded as described in the <ref target="#languageCodes">Recording Language Information (<att>xml:lang</att>)</ref>
                section, above
              </p>
              <p>
                Abstracts must also have a <att>corresp</att> attribute that contains one or more
                space-separated URIs that correspond to the <gi>idno</gi> element in the
                  <gi>seriesStmt</gi> elements. These URIs identify <title>NHSL</title> and its
                sub-volumes, such as the <title>Bibliotheca Hagiographica Syriaca Electronica</title>. 
                If there are multiple abstracts, only one can reference a given
                series URI, and every series URI must be referenced by one of the abstracts.
                <!--Example of a rec with multiple, distinct? -->
              </p>
          </div>
          <div xml:id="note">
            <head>Scholarly Annotation</head>
            <p>
              <!--
              - scope, versions, content, disambiguation notes
              -->
            </p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <head>Prologues, Incipits, Excerpts, and Explicits (<gi>noteGrp</gi>)</head>
            <p>To assist users with disambiguating similar works, textual excerpts of various
              types may be included.
              <!--
              TBD: stopped here
              -->
            <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
              <noteGrp type="incipit">
                <desc xml:lang="en">Incipit</desc>
                <note xml:lang="syr" type="incipit">
                  <quote source="#bib567-1">ܨܒܿܬܗ ܫܡܘܐܝܠ ܠܫܪܪܟ ܕܐܣܗܕ ܗܘܐ ܦܘܡܗ ܠܥܡܐ</quote>
                </note>
                <note xml:lang="fr" type="incipit">
                  <quote source="#bib567-1">Samuel a orné ta vérité, lui dont la bouche avait
                    fait témoigner le peuple.</quote>
                </note>
              </noteGrp>
            </egXML>
            <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
              <noteGrp type="prologue">
                <desc xml:lang="en">Prologue</desc>
                <note xml:lang="syr" type="prologue">
                  <quote source="#bib1-1">ܒܫܡ ܡܪܝܐ ܐܚܝ̣ܕ ܟܠ ܡܫ̣ܪܝܢܢ ܕܢܚ̣ܬܘ̇ܡ ܟܬܒܐ ܕܐܘܪܝܬܐ ܕܡܘܫܐ
                    ܢܒܝܐ</quote>
                </note>
              </noteGrp>
              <noteGrp type="incipit">
                <desc xml:lang="en">Incipit</desc>
                <note xml:lang="syr" type="incipit">
                  <quote source="#bib1-3">ܒܪܫܝܬ ܒܪܐ ܐܠܗܐ܂ ܝܬ ܫܡܝܐ ܘܝܬ ܐܪܥܐ܂</quote>
                </note>
              </noteGrp>
            </egXML>
            </p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div xml:id="listRelation">
            <head>Relations (<gi>listRelation</gi>)</head>
            <p><title>NHSL</title> records can express structured relationships between a work and
              other entities in the Syriaca.org knowledge graph. These relationships are encoded
              using a <gi>listRelation</gi> element containing one or more <gi>relation</gi>
              elements. The <gi>listRelation</gi> element appears as a direct child of the
              <gi>bibl</gi> element.</p>
            <p>Each <gi>relation</gi> element has the following required attributes:</p>
            <list>
              <item><att>ref</att> — the URI of the relationship predicate, drawn from a standard
                ontology vocabulary (SKOS, Dublin Core Terms, or the Syriaca.org namespace)</item>
              <item><att>active</att> — the URI of the subject of the relationship (in most cases,
                the URI of the current work)</item>
              <item><att>passive</att> — the URI of the object of the relationship</item>
            </list>
            <p>Optionally, a <att>source</att> attribute may supply a bibliographic citation, and a
              child <gi>desc</gi> element may provide a human-readable description of the
              relationship.</p>

            <div xml:id="broaderRelation">
              <head>Work-to-Tradition Relationship (<code>skos:broader</code>)</head>
              <p>The relationship between a specific conceptual work and its broader literary
                tradition is expressed using <code>skos:broader</code>. The active URI is the
                specific work; the passive URI is the literary tradition record:</p>
              <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                <listRelation>
                  <relation ref="skos:broader" active="http://syriaca.org/work/1"
                    passive="http://syriaca.org/work/9628">
                    <desc xml:lang="en">
                      <title ref="http://syriaca.org/work/9628">Genesis (literary tradition)</title>
                    </desc>
                  </relation>
                </listRelation>
              </egXML>
              <p>This relation is always placed on the more specific <code>lawd:ConceptualWork</code>
                record (with the literary tradition as the passive/broader concept), not on the
                <code>syriaca:LiteraryTradition</code> record.</p>
            </div>

            <div xml:id="partRelation">
              <head>Part-Whole Relationships (<code>dcterms:isPartOf</code>)</head>
              <p>When a work is part of a larger work or collection — for example, when the book of
                Genesis is part of the Pentateuch, or when a hagiographic text is a chapter within
                a larger collection — this is expressed using <code>dcterms:isPartOf</code>. A
                <att>type</att> attribute with the value <q>part</q> is required on the
                <gi>relation</gi> element. A child <gi>desc</gi>/<gi>label</gi> may specify the
                ordering of the work within the larger collection:</p>
              <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                <relation type="part" ref="dcterms:isPartOf" active="http://syriaca.org/work/1"
                  passive="http://syriaca.org/work/68" source="#bib1-24 #bib1-26">
                  <desc xml:lang="en">
                    <label type="order" subtype="book" n="1" source="#bib1-24 #bib1-26">book 1</label>
                  </desc>
                </relation>
              </egXML>
              <p>The <gi>label</gi> element within <gi>desc</gi> records the ordering of the work
                within its parent. The <att>subtype</att> attribute indicates the unit of ordering
                (e.g., <q>book</q>, <q>part</q>), and the <att>n</att> attribute gives the
                ordinal number.</p>
            </div>

            <div xml:id="commemoratesRelation">
              <head>Hagiographic Subjects (<code>syriaca:commemorates</code>)</head>
              <p>For hagiographic texts, the person who is commemorated (the subject saint or
                martyr) is linked using the <code>syriaca:commemorates</code> relationship. The
                active URI is the work; the passive URI is the Syriaca.org person URI for the
                commemorated individual:</p>
              <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                <listRelation>
                  <relation ref="syriaca:commemorates" active="http://syriaca.org/work/567"
                    source="#bib567-1" passive="http://syriaca.org/person/1113">
                    <desc xml:lang="en">
                      <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/1113">Abraham Qidounaya</persName>
                    </desc>
                  </relation>
                </listRelation>
              </egXML>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div xml:id="listBibl">
            <head>Bibliography Related to the Work(<gi>listBibl</gi>)</head>
            <p>The bibliographic information related to the work is organized into sections describing editions, manuscripts, modern translations, ancient versions, and secondary sources. These classifications are derived from the IFLA LRM entities "expression", "manifestation", and "item". For example, editions and manuscripts contain particular "expressions" and "manifestations" of the work. Translations and versions are "expressions" that are different from the Syriac language "expression" of the work. Each of these expressions" and "manifestations" are identified through particular bibliographic "items" for which a publication citation, manuscript shelmark, or other bibliographic information is provided. Each section is encoded as a
              separate <gi>listBibl</gi> element with a <att>type</att> attribute identifying the
              category. These sections are each <gi>listBibl</gi> element begins with a <gi>head</gi> element
              providing the category label, followed by a <gi>desc</gi> element describing the scope of the bibliography, followed by the individual <gi>bibl</gi> elements for each item. Users of <title>NHSL</title> should note that these bibliographic sections are not necessarily exhaustive. <title>NHSL</title> is published as part of the Syriaca.org linked data graph, so there may be other bibliography related to each literary work which can be found through the <title>Comprehensive Bibliographty on Syriac Studies</title>.</p>

            <div xml:id="editions">
              <head>Editions (<gi>listBibl type="editions"</gi>)</head>
              <p>Consulting published editions of Syriac texts is one of the most comprehensive ways to identify a distinct literary work, especially if the published text is a critical edition with apparatus. Accordingly, at the time of composition <title>NHSL</title> entries should try to cite all printed editions of the work (including diplomatic and eclectic editions). Because of the constant publication of new scholarship, however, readers should not assume that the list of editions is complete in any given record (a prewritten <gi>desc</gi> element is provided with a note to this effect).</p> 
              <p>The <gi>listBibl type="editions"</gi> section records the citations for editions of
                the work. Each edition is encoded as a separate <gi>bibl</gi> element with
                <code>type="lawd:Edition"</code>. Each <gi>bibl</gi> must be assigned a unique <att>xml:id<att> as documented above. Because Syriaca.org manages the publication information for all citations in a separate
                reference work, <ref target="https://syriaca.org/cbss/index.html"><title>The
                    Comprehensive Bibliography on Syriac Studies (CBSS)</title></ref>, it is not necessary to include the full citation in the <gi>bibl</gi> element. Instead,
                the first step in adding a citation for an edition into a work record in <title>NSHL</title> is to
                identify the corresponding entry in <title>CBSS</title>.</p><p>Users can search the
                bibliography at <ref target="https://syriaca.org/cbss/search.html"
                  >https://syriaca.org/cbss/search.html</ref>. Once the item to be cited is located,
                editors should note the URI for the bibliographic item. This URI will have the
                format <code>http://syriaca.org/cbss/[A-Z0-9]{8}$</code> (where
                  <code>"[A-Z0-9]{8}$"</code> signifies a unique string of 8 uppercase alphanumeric
                characters). For example, the URI for J.B. Segal, <title>Edessa, ‘The Blessed
                  City’</title> (Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1970) is <ref
                  target="http://syriaca.org/cbss/FQCVBMNS"
                    ><code>http://syriaca.org/cbss/FQCVBMNS</code></ref>. If the desired
                bibliographic item is not found in <title>CBSS</title>, editors should request the
                creation of an entry in <title>CBSS</title>.</p>
                <p>Once the editor has identified the CBSS URI, they may proceed to encoding the edition citation in <title>NSHL</title>. The <gi>bibl</gi> element must include a
                title (<gi>title</gi>) and a pointer
                (<gi>ptr</gi>) to the URI of the CBSS bibliographic URI, and one or more
                <gi>citedRange</gi> elements specifying the location within the edition where
                the text appears.</p><p><emph>Nota bene</emph>: The contents of the <gi>title</gi> are for reference purposes within the XML document only. When XML file is converted for publication online, the GADDEL app will use the CBSS URI to look up the full citation in <title>CBSS</title> and insert it into the record. Special care should be taken to include the  <gi>citedRange</gi> because that information is unique and cannot be inserted based on the CBS URI.</p>
                <p>The following information should be encoded using attribute values within the <gi>bibl</gi> or its descendants. <title>NSHL</title> records are required to cite their sources using either the <att>source</att> or
                <att>resp</att> attributes as described above. If the information about an edition is derived from another source (such as Zanetti and Detienne, <title>Bibliotheca Hagiographica Syriaca</title>) then that other source should be cited using <att>source</att>. If the edition itself has been consulted directly by the Syriaca.org editor, then an <att>resp</att> should be used with the value <q>http://syriaca.org</q> to indicate that the editors of <title>NSHL</title> are responsible for the inclusion of the citation rather than creating a circular citation back to the edition itself (see the section above <ref target="resp">Asserting
                Information without a Source (<att>resp</att>)</ref>).</p>
                <p>Other information encoded as attributes includes <att>unit</att> on <gi>citedRange</gi> and <att>xml:lang</att> on <gi>title</gi> as described above.</p>
                <p> Here is an example of an edition citation from work record<ref
                  target="http://syriaca.org/work/567"
                    ><code>http://syriaca.org/work/567</code></ref> :</p>
              <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                <listBibl type="editions">
                  <head>Editions</head>
                  <desc xml:lang="en">This is not a comprehensive list of editions related to
                    this work.</desc>
                  <bibl source="#bib567-1" xml:id="bib567-3" type="lawd:Edition">
                    <title xml:lang="de">Des heiligen Ephraem des Syrers Hymnen auf Abraham
                      Kidunaya und Julianos Saba</title>
                    <ptr target="http://syriaca.org/cbss/YN3NJHST"/>
                    <citedRange unit="p">3-6</citedRange>
                  </bibl>
                </listBibl>
              </egXML>
              <div xml:id="editionManuscriptLink">
                <head>Linking Editions to Manuscripts <gi>relation type="mssWitnesses" ref="dcterms:source"</gi></head>
                <p>Within an edition's <gi>bibl</gi> entry, a nested <gi>listRelation</gi> may
                  record the manuscript(s) used as the base text(s) for that edition. This is
                  expressed using a <gi>relation</gi> with <code>type="mssWitnesses"</code> and
                  <code>ref="dcterms:source"</code>. The <att>active</att> attribute refers to the
                  xml:id of the edition entry (with the
                  <code>#</code> prefix); the <att>passive</att> attribute gives the xml:id of the manuscript entry (with the
                  <code>#</code> prefix) found in the manuscripts section of the same record. A
                  <gi>desc</gi>/<gi>label</gi> provides a human-readable shelfmark in a <gi>desc</gi> following the format described below (see <ref="#manuscripts">Manuscripts</ref>:
                </p>
                <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                  <listRelation>
                    <relation type="mssWitnesses" ref="dcterms:source" active="bib836-2"
                      source="#bib836-1" passive="#bib836-4">
                      <desc xml:lang="en">
                        <label>London, British Library <idno type="shelfmark"
                            subtype="BL">Add. 14647</idno></label>
                      </desc>
                    </relation>
                  </listRelation>
                </egXML>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div xml:id="manuscripts">
              <head>Manuscripts (<gi>listBibl type="manuscripts"</gi>)</head>
              <p>The <gi>listBibl type="manuscripts"</gi> section records the manuscripts known to
                contain the work. Each manuscript entry is a <gi>bibl</gi> element with
                <code>type="syriaca:Manuscript"</code>. A manuscript entry should include one or
                more <gi>label</gi> elements providing the human-readable identification of the
                manuscript (library, collection, shelfmark), and may include a <gi>ptr</gi>
                linking to the manuscript's record in the <ref
                  target="https://syriaca.org/manuscripts"><title>Syriaca.org Manuscript
                    Catalogue</title></ref>, a <gi>biblScope</gi> specifying the folios where the
                work appears, and a <gi>date</gi> or <gi>date</gi> range indicating the date of
                the manuscript:</p>
              <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                <listBibl type="manuscripts">
                  <head>Manuscripts</head>
                  <desc xml:lang="en">This is not a comprehensive list of manuscripts related to
                    this work. Further citations may be available through Syriac.Nexus.</desc>
                  <bibl type="syriaca:Manuscript" xml:id="bib1-12" source="#bib1-20 #bib1-21">
                    <label>London, British Library, Add MS 12172</label>
                    <ptr target="http://syriaca.org/manuscript/1182"/>
                    <biblScope unit="fol" from="136b" to="164">Foll. 136b-164</biblScope>
                    <date notBefore="0800" notAfter="1000">9th-10th century</date>
                  </bibl>
                  <bibl xml:id="bib836-4" source="#bib836-1" type="syriaca:Manuscript">
                    <label>London, British Library <idno type="shelfmark"
                        subtype="BL">Add. 14647</idno></label>
                    <biblScope unit="fol">f. 109v-110v</biblScope>
                  </bibl>
                </listBibl>
              </egXML>
              <p>The <gi>label</gi> element may contain an <gi>idno</gi> child for the shelfmark,
                with a <att>type</att> of <q>shelfmark</q> and a <att>subtype</att> identifying
                the library (e.g., <q>BL</q> for British Library, <q>BNF</q> for Bibliothèque
                nationale de France, <q>BAV</q> for Biblioteca Apostolica Vaticana). When a
                manuscript has a known Syriaca.org URI, the <gi>ptr</gi> element should link to
                it. Dates for manuscripts use the standard <att>notBefore</att> and
                <att>notAfter</att> attributes for date ranges, or <att>when</att> for exact
                dates. Dates must be expressed in ISO 8601 format (four-digit year, with leading
                zeroes for dates before CE 1000).</p>
              <p>When the work is defective in a particular manuscript witness, this may be noted
                with a <gi>note</gi> element:
              </p>
              <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                <bibl type="syriaca:Manuscript" xml:id="bib1-15" source="#bib1-26 #bib1-27">
                  <label>London, British Library, Add MS 14671</label>
                  <ptr target="http://syriaca.org/manuscript/523"/>
                  <biblScope unit="fol" from="1a" to="42">Foll. 1a to 42</biblScope>
                  <date notBefore="1200" notAfter="1300">13th century</date>
                  <note xml:lang="en" resp="http://syriaca.org">defective</note>
                </bibl>
              </egXML>
            </div>

            <div xml:id="modernTranslations">
              <head>Modern Translations (<gi>listBibl type="modernTranslations"</gi>)</head>
              <p>The <gi>listBibl type="modernTranslations"</gi> section records modern scholarly
                translations of the work into contemporary languages. Each translation is encoded
                as a <gi>bibl</gi> element with <code>type="syriaca:ModernTranslation"</code>.
                The entry should include the editor(s) of the translation, a <gi>ptr</gi> to the
                <title>CBSS</title> record for the publication, <gi>citedRange</gi> elements for
                the location within the publication, and a <gi>textLang</gi> element with a
                <att>mainLang</att> attribute indicating the language of the translation:</p>
              <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                <listBibl type="modernTranslations">
                  <head>Modern Translations</head>
                  <desc xml:lang="en">This is not a comprehensive list of modern translations
                    related to this work. Further citations may be available through Syriac.Nexus.</desc>
                  <bibl xml:id="bib567-9" source="#bib567-1" type="syriaca:ModernTranslation">
                    <title xml:lang="la">CSCO 323 Script. Syri 141</title>
                    <editor>E. Beck</editor>
                    <ptr target="http://syriaca.org/cbss/LX56D4IQ"/>
                    <citedRange unit="p">3-7</citedRange>
                    <textLang mainLang="de"/>
                  </bibl>
                </listBibl>
              </egXML>
            </div>

            <div xml:id="secondaryLiterature">
              <head>Secondary Literature (<gi>listBibl type="secondaryLiterature"</gi>)</head>
              <p>The <gi>listBibl type="secondaryLiterature"</gi> section serves two distinct
                purposes in <title>NHSL</title> records. First, it records scholarly secondary
                literature about the work. Second — and equally important — it functions as the
                <q>Works Cited</q> section for the entire record: all <gi>bibl</gi> entries in
                this section may be referenced via the <att>source</att> attribute on any element
                elsewhere in the document that requires bibliographic citation.</p>
              <p>Each secondary literature entry is encoded as a <gi>bibl</gi> element with
                <code>type="lawd:Citation"</code>. Each entry must have an <att>xml:id</att>
                following the pattern <code>bib[workNum]-[n]</code>. At minimum, a secondary
                literature entry must include a <gi>ptr</gi> pointing to the item's <title>CBSS</title>
                URI, and a <gi>citedRange</gi> element specifying the exact location within that
                work where information relevant to the current record can be found:</p>
              <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                <listBibl type="secondaryLiterature">
                  <head>Secondary Literature</head>
                  <desc xml:lang="en">This is not a comprehensive list of secondary literature
                    related to this work. Further citations may be available through Syriac.Nexus.</desc>
                  <bibl type="lawd:Citation" xml:id="bib567-1">
                    <title level="m" xml:lang="la">Bibliotheca Hagiographica Syriaca</title>
                    <ptr target="http://syriaca.org/cbss/2KJEZZGS"/>
                    <citedRange unit="entry">347</citedRange>
                  </bibl>
                  <bibl type="lawd:Citation" xml:id="bib567-2">
                    <title xml:lang="en" level="a">Theological progress and artistic regress in
                      the hymns on Abraham Kidunaya attributed to St Ephrem</title>
                    <title level="j" xml:lang="la">Acta Patristica et Byzantina</title>
                    <ptr target="http://syriaca.org/cbss/45KYLSW7"/>
                    <citedRange from="77" to="98" unit="p">77-98</citedRange>
                  </bibl>
                </listBibl>
              </egXML>
              <p>This dual role of the <gi>listBibl type="secondaryLiterature"</gi> section means
                that it will typically include the principal reference work from which the record
                data was derived (such as the relevant <title>BHS</title> entry, or an edition
                catalogue), as well as any additional secondary scholarship cited elsewhere in
                the record. The order of entries within this section does not reflect the order
                of citation; rather, entries are numbered sequentially according to when they
                were added to the record.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div xml:id="schema">
        <head>NHSL TEI P5 Schema Customization</head>
        <schemaSpec ident="syriacaWorks" prefix="tei_" source="syriacaAll.compiled.odd" xml:lang="en" defaultExceptions="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0 teix:egXML​ http://www.example.org/ns/">
        <moduleRef key="core" include="author bibl biblScope citedRange date desc editor 
          foreign head label listBibl name note noteGrp p ptr quote ref resp respStmt textLang title"/>
        <moduleRef key="header" include="authority availability catDesc category 
          change classDecl edition editionStmt editorialDecl encodingDesc 
          fileDesc funder idno interpretation langUsage licence profileDesc 
          publicationStmt revisionDesc seriesStmt sourceDesc sponsor taxonomy
          teiHeader titleStmt"/>
        <moduleRef key="namesdates" include="listRelation persName placeName relation"/>
        <moduleRef key="tei"/>
        <moduleRef key="textstructure" include="body text TEI"/>
        <classRef key="att.personal"/>
        <classRef key="att.global.analytic"/>
        <classRef key="att.global.change"/>
        <classRef key="att.global.linking"/>
        
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="author" module="core" mode="change">
          <constraintSpec ident="ref-on-author" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body/child::tei:bibl/child::tei:author">
                <sch:assert test="matches(@ref, concat('http://syriaca.org/person/', '\d+'))" role="error">
                  This &lt;author&gt; element must take a @ref attribute 
                  with a Syriaca.org person URI which reqires 
                  the form 'http://syriaca.org/person/{\d+}' (where {\d+} is a number).
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <constraintSpec ident="author-in-context" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body/child::tei:bibl/child::tei:author">
                <sch:report test="tei:persName">
                  This &lt;author&gt; element allows only a text node with an English name 
                  or a &lt;foreign&gt; element with a non-English name.
                </sch:report>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <!--<elementSpec ident="authority" module="header" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>
          
          
          
          <elementSpec ident="availability" module="header" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>-->
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="bibl" module="core" mode="change">
          <content>
            <sequence preserveOrder="true">
              <elementRef key="title" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="author" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="editor" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="idno" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="label" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="ptr" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="citedRange" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="biblScope" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="textLang" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="date" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="noteGrp" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="note" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="listRelation" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="listBibl" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
            </sequence>
          </content>
          <constraintSpec ident="bibl-in-context" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/tei:bibl">
                <sch:assert test="tei:label">
                  <!-- Add the requirement of a ptr once we have those mss records in place. -->
                  A manuscript &lt;bibl&gt; element must have a child &lt;label&gt; element.
                </sch:assert>
                <sch:assert test="@type='syriaca:Manuscript'">
                  This &lt;bibl&gt; element requires a @type attribute with the value "syriaca:Manuscript".
                </sch:assert>
                <sch:report test="@ana">
                  The @ana attribute is not allowed here.
                </sch:report>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:listBibl[@type='ancientVersions']/tei:bibl">
                <sch:assert test="tei:label or tei:ptr">
                  An ancient versions &lt;bibl&gt; element must have eith a child &lt;label&gt; element
                  or a child &lt;ptr&lt; element.
                </sch:assert>
                <sch:assert test="@type='syriaca:AncientVersion'">
                  This &lt;bibl&gt; element requires a @type attribute with the value "syriaca:AncientVersion".
                </sch:assert>
                <sch:report test="@ana">
                  The @ana attribute is not allowed here.
                </sch:report>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:listBibl[@type='editions']/tei:bibl">
                <sch:assert test="@type='lawd:Edition'">
                  This &lt;bibl&gt; element requires a @type attribute with the value "lawd:Edition".
                </sch:assert>
                <sch:assert test="tei:ptr">
                  An edition &lt;bibl&gt; element must have a child &lt;ptr&gt; element.
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:listBibl[@type='modernTranslations']/tei:bibl">
                <sch:assert test="@type='syriaca:ModernTranslation'">
                  This &lt;bibl&gt; element requires a @type attribute with the value "syriaca:ModernTranslation".
                </sch:assert>
                <sch:assert test="tei:ptr or tei:label">
                  A modern translation &lt;bibl&gt; element must have either a child &lt;ptr&gt; element or
                  a child &lt;label&gt; element. The &lt;label&gt; element should only be used in the 
                  rare instance where the modern translation is contained in a manuscript.
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:listBibl[@type='secondaryLiterature']/tei:bibl">
                <sch:assert test="@type='lawd:Citation'">
                  This &lt;bibl&gt; element requires a @type attribute with the value "lawd:Citation".
                </sch:assert>
                <sch:assert test="tei:ptr">
                  A secondary literature &lt;bibl&gt; element must have a child &lt;ptr&gt; element.
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body/child::tei:bibl">
                <sch:assert test="tei:title and tei:idno and tei:listBibl">
                  Every work-level &lt;bibl&gt; element must have as child elements at least &lt;title&gt;, 
                  &lt;idno&gt;, and &lt;listBibl&gt;.
                </sch:assert>
                <sch:report test="tei:note">
                  Notes under a work &lt;bibl&gt; must be encoded in a &lt;noteGrp&gt; element.
                </sch:report>
                <sch:report test="tei:bibl">
                  Bibliography under a work &lt;bibl&gt; must be encoded in a &lt;listBibl&gt; element.
                </sch:report>
                <sch:report test="tei:label">
                  The work &lt;bibl&gt; does not take a child &lt;label&gt; element.
                </sch:report>
                <sch:assert test="@xml:id">
                  The main work &lt;bibl&gt; must have an @xml:id.
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body/child::tei:bibl/@xml:id">
                <sch:let name="docURIno" value="replace(//tei:publicationStmt/tei:idno[@type='URI'][not(@type='deprecated')]/text(), '.+?(\d+).+', '$1')"/>
                <sch:let name="id" value="@xml:id"/>
                <sch:assert test="matches(., concat('work-', $docURIno))">
                  The required @xml:id must be 'work-<sch:value-of select="$docURIno"/>.
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:listBibl//tei:bibl">
                <sch:let name="docURIno" value="replace(//tei:publicationStmt/tei:idno[@type='URI'][not(@type='deprecated')]/text(), '.+?(\d+).+', '$1')"/>
                <sch:let name="id" value="@xml:id"/>
                <!-- The following rule isn't working to require an @xml:id on all listBibl/bibl elements. Should it? -->
                <sch:assert test="matches(./@xml:id, concat('bib', $docURIno, '-', '\d+$'))">
                  The required @xml:id must be 'bib<sch:value-of select="$docURIno"/>-{\d+}' (where {\d+} is a number).
                </sch:assert>
                <sch:report test="preceding-sibling::element()[@xml:id = $id]">This @xml:id is already in use.</sch:report>
                <sch:report test="tei:noteGrp">
                  Notes encoded inside a &lt;listBibl&gt; cannot appear inside a &lt;noteGrp&gt; element.
                </sch:report>
                <sch:report test="tei:listBibl">
                  Bibliography encoded inside a &lt;listBibl&gt; cannot appear inside a &lt;listBibl&gt; element.
                </sch:report>
                <sch:report test="tei:idno">
                  In this context, a &lt;idno&gt; element must appear as the child of a 
                  &lt;label&gt; element.
                </sch:report>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <constraintSpec ident="work-bhse" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body/child::tei:bibl[contains(@ana, '#syriaca-hagiographic')]">
                <sch:assert test="//tei:seriesStmt/tei:title = 'Bibliotheca Hagiographica Syriaca Electronica'">
                  This work record must include a &lt;seriesStmt&gt; indicating that it is part of the volume 
                  "Bibliotheca Hagiographica Syriaca Electronica".
                </sch:assert>
                <sch:assert test="//tei:seriesStmt/tei:title = 'Gateway to the Syriac Saints'">
                  This work record must include a &lt;seriesStmt&gt; indicating that it is part of the 
                  series "Gateway to the Syriac Saints".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:TEI[//tei:seriesStmt/tei:title = 'Gateway to the Syriac Saints']//tei:body/child::tei:bibl">
                <sch:assert test="contains(@ana, '#syriaca-hagiographic')">
                  A work &lt;bibl&gt; that is part of the series "Gateway to the Syriac Saints" must have an 
                  @ana attribute with the value "#syriaca-hagiographic".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:TEI[//tei:seriesStmt/tei:title = 'Bibliotheca Hagiographica Syriaca Electronica']//tei:body/child::tei:bibl">
                <sch:assert test="contains(@ana, '#syriaca-hagiographic')">
                  A work &lt;bibl&gt; that is part of the series "Bibliotheca Hagiographica Syriaca Electronica" must have an 
                  @ana attribute with the value "#syriaca-hagiographic".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <constraintSpec ident="work-bible" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body/child::tei:bibl[contains(@ana, '#syriaca-biblical')]">
                <sch:assert test="//tei:seriesStmt/tei:title = 'A Guide to the Bible in Syriac'">
                  This work record must include a &lt;seriesStmt&gt; indicating that it is part of the volume 
                  "A Guide to the Bible in Syriac".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:TEI[//tei:seriesStmt/tei:title = 'A Guide to the Bible in Syriac']//tei:body/child::tei:bibl">
                <sch:assert test="contains(@ana, '#syriaca-biblical')">
                  A work &lt;bibl&gt; that is part of the series "A Guide to the Bible in Syriac" must have an 
                  @ana attribute with the value "#syriaca-biblical".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <constraintSpec ident="work-science" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body/child::tei:bibl[contains(@ana, '#syriaca-scientific')]">
                <sch:assert test="//tei:seriesStmt/tei:title = 'Syriac Scientific and Philosophical Literature'">
                  This work record must include a &lt;seriesStmt&gt; indicating that it is part of the volume 
                  "Syriac Scientific and Philosophical Literature".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:TEI[//tei:seriesStmt/tei:title = 'Syriac Scientific and Philosophical Literature']//tei:body/child::tei:bibl">
                <sch:assert test="contains(@ana, '#syriaca-scientific')">
                  A work &lt;bibl&gt; that is part of the series "Syriac Scientific and Philosophical Literature" must have an 
                  @ana attribute with the value "#syriaca-scientific".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <constraintSpec ident="bibl-child-bibl" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:bibl//tei:bibl">
                <sch:report test="tei:listBibl">
                  This &lt;bibl&gt; element cannot take a child &lt;listBibl&gt;.
                </sch:report>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <attList>
            <attDef ident="type" mode="replace">
              <valList type="closed">
                <valItem ident="lawd:Citation"/>
                <valItem ident="lawd:Edition"/>
                <valItem ident="lawd:ConceptualWork"/>
                <valItem ident="lawd:Edition"/>
                <valItem ident="syriaca:AncientVersion"/>
                <valItem ident="syriaca:DigitalCatalog"/>
                <valItem ident="syriaca:LiteraryTradition"/>
                <valItem ident="syriaca:Manuscript"/>
                <valItem ident="syriaca:ModernTranslation"/>
                <valItem ident="syriaca:PrintCatalog"/>
              </valList>
            </attDef>
            <attDef ident="ana" mode="change">
              <!-- Not sure we want to do this? -->
              <valList type="closed">
                <valItem ident="#syriaca-biblical"/>
                <valItem ident="#syriaca-hagiographic"/>
                <valItem ident="#syriaca-scientific"/>
              </valList>
            </attDef>
          </attList>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="biblScope" module="core" mode="change">
          
          <content>
            <sequence preserveOrder="false">
              <textNode/>
              <elementRef key="idno" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="title" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
            </sequence>
          </content>
          <attList>
            <attDef ident="unit" mode="change" usage="req">
              <valList type="closed" mode="replace">
                <valItem ident="cah"/>
                <valItem ident="fol"/>
                <valItem ident="p"/>
                <valItem ident="vol"/>
              </valList>
            </attDef>
            <!-- Look into @n, @from, @to -->
          </attList>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="body" module="textstructure" mode="change">
          <content>
            <elementRef key="bibl" minOccurs="1" maxOccurs="1"/>
          </content>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="catDesc" module="header" mode="change">
          
          <content>
            <sequence preserveOrder="false">
              <textNode/>
              <elementRef key="ref" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
            </sequence>
          </content>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="category" module="header" mode="change">
          
          <content>
            <elementRef key="catDesc" minOccurs="1"/>
          </content>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="change" module="header" mode="change">
          
          <content>
            <sequence preserveOrder="false">
              <textNode/>
              <elementRef key="ref" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
            </sequence>
          </content>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <!--<elementSpec ident="citedRange" module="core" mode="change">
          
          
          </elementSpec>-->
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="classDecl" module="header" mode="change">
          <content>
            <elementRef key="taxonomy" minOccurs="1" maxOccurs="1"/>
          </content>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="date" module="core" mode="change">
          <content>
            <textNode/>
          </content>
          <attList>
            <!-- Regarding @calendar and @datingMethod, see SPEAR ODD -->
            <attDef ident="type" mode="change" usage="rec">
              <!-- might need to revisit this -->
              <desc>specifies how the date is associated with the work to
                which it refers</desc>
              <valList mode="replace" type="closed">
                <valItem ident="original-composition">
                  <desc>the date a work was originally composed</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="revision">
                  <desc>the date a work was revised</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="translation">
                  <desc>the date a work was translated</desc>
                </valItem>
              </valList>
            </attDef>
          </attList>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="desc" module="core" mode="change">
          <content>
            <sequence preserveOrder="false">
              <textNode/>
              <elementRef key="label" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="1"/>
              <elementRef key="persName" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="1"/>
              <elementRef key="placeName" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="1"/>
              <elementRef key="title" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="1"/>
            </sequence>
          </content>
          <constraintSpec ident="noteGrp-desc-values" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:noteGrp[@type='abstract']/tei:desc">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'Abstract'">Text node must be "Abstract".</sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:noteGrp[@type='contents']/tei:desc">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'Contents'">Text node must be "Contents".</sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:noteGrp[@type='excerpts']/tei:desc">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'Excerpts'">Text node must be "Excerpts".</sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:noteGrp[@type='disambiguation']/tei:desc">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'Disambiguation'">Text node must be "Disambiguation".</sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:noteGrp[@type='excerpts']/tei:desc">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'Excerpts'">Text node must be "Excerpt".</sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:noteGrp[@type='explicit']/tei:desc">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'Explicit'">Text node must be "Explicit".</sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:noteGrp[@type='incipit']/tei:desc">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'Incipit'">Text node must be "Incipit".</sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:noteGrp[@type='prologue']/tei:desc">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'Prologue'">Text node must be "Prologue".</sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:noteGrp[@type='scope']/tei:desc">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'Scope'">Text node must be "Scope".</sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:noteGrp[@type='versions']/tei:desc">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'Ancient Versions'">Text node must be "Versions".</sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <!--<elementSpec ident="editionStmt" module="header" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>-->
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="editor" module="core" mode="change">
          <constraintSpec ident="ref-on-editor" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body/child::tei:bibl/child::tei:editor">
                <sch:assert test="matches(@ref, concat('http://syriaca.org/person/', '\d+'))" role="error">
                  This &lt;editor&gt; element must take a @ref attribute 
                  with a Syriaca.org person URI which reqires 
                  the form 'http://syriaca.org/person/{\d+}' (where {\d+} is a number).
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <constraintSpec ident="editor-in-context" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body/child::tei:bibl/child::tei:editor">
                <sch:report test="tei:persName">
                  This &lt;author&gt; element allows only a text node with an English name 
                  or a &lt;foreign&gt; element with a non-English name.
                </sch:report>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <!--<elementSpec ident="editorialDecl" module="header" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>-->
        
        
        
        <!--<elementSpec ident="encodingDesc" module="header" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>-->
        
        
        
        <!--<elementSpec ident="fileDesc" module="header" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>-->
        
        
        
        <!--<elementSpec ident="foreign" module="core" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>-->
        
        
        
        <!--<elementSpec ident="funder" module="header" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>-->
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="head" module="core" mode="change">
          <content>
            <textNode/>
          </content>
          <constraintSpec ident="listBibl-head-values" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='editions']/tei:head">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'Editions'">Text node must be "Editions".</sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/tei:head">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'Manuscripts'">Text node must be "Manuscripts".</sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='modernTranslations']/tei:head">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'Modern Translations'">Text node must be "Modern Translations".</sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='ancientVersions']/tei:head">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'Ancient Versions'">Text node must be "Ancient Version".</sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='secondaryLiterature']/tei:head">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'Secondary Literature'">Text node must be "Secondary Literature".</sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="idno" module="header" mode="change">
          <content>
            <textNode/>
          </content>
          <constraintSpec ident="work-idno-types" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body/child::tei:bibl/child::tei:idno/@type">
                <sch:assert test=". = ('deprecated', 'number', 'URI', 'URN')">
                  The only acceptable values for @type on a work &lt;idno&gt; are "deprecated", "number", 
                  "URI" or "URN". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body/child::tei:bibl/child::tei:idno[1]">
                <sch:let name="workURI" value="substring-before(//tei:publicationStmt/tei:idno[@type='URI'][not(@type='deprecated')]/text(), '/tei')"/>
                <sch:assert test=". = $workURI">
                  The text node of this &lt;idno&gt; element must be <sch:value-of select="$workURI"/>. 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/tei:bibl/tei:label/tei:idno/@type">
                <sch:assert test=". = ('accession-number', 'catalog-number', 'number', 'project-number', 'shelfmark', 'URL')">
                  In the context of manuscripts, this @type value may only be "accession-number", "number",
                  "project-number", or "shelfmark". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/tei:bibl/tei:label/tei:idno[@subtype='Bekker' or @subtype='CPG' or @subtype='Fichtner']/@type">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'number'">
                  When an &lt;indo&gt; has @subtype="<sch:value-of select="./parent::tei:idno/@subtype"/>", 
                  the @type value must be "number".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/tei:bibl/tei:label/tei:idno[@subtype='BAV' or @subtype='BML' or @subtype='UCL']/@type">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'shelfmark'">
                  When an &lt;indo&gt; has @subtype="<sch:value-of select="./parent::tei:idno/@subtype"/>", 
                  the @type value must be "shelfmark".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/tei:bibl/tei:label/tei:idno[@subtype='HMML']/@type">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'project-number'">
                  When an &lt;indo&gt; has @subtype="<sch:value-of select="./parent::tei:idno/@subtype"/>", 
                  the @type value must be "project-number".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/tei:bibl/tei:label/tei:idno[@subtype='Rosen']/@type">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'catalog-number'">
                  When an &lt;indo&gt; has @subtype="<sch:value-of select="./parent::tei:idno/@subtype"/>", 
                  the @type value must be "catalog-number".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <constraintSpec ident="idno-subtypes" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body/child::tei:bibl/child::tei:idno[@type='number']/@subtype">
                <sch:assert test=". = ('Bekker', 'BHO', 'BHS', 'CPG', 'Fichtner', 'Kühn', 'Takahashi')">
                  The only acceptable values for @subtype on a work &lt;idno&gt; with @type="number" are 
                  "Bekker", "BHO", "BHS", "CPG", "Fichtner", "Kühn", and "Takahashi". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/tei:bibl/tei:label/tei:idno/@subtype" role="warning">
                <sch:assert test=". = ('BAV', 'BL', 'BML', 'BNF', 'Berlin', 'Cambridge', 'Crawford', 'Haddad-Isaac', 'Harris', 'HMML', 'Leiden', 'Mingana', 'Rosen', 'SOAH', 'Sachau', 'Sinai', 'UCL')">
                  In the context of manuscripts, this @subtype value may only be 
                  "BAV" (for the Vatican Apostolic Library), "BML" (for The Laurentian Library), 
                  "Berlin", "Cambridge", "Crawford", "Haddad-Isaac", "Harris", "HMML", 
                  "Leiden", "Mingana", "Rosen", "SOAH", "Sachau", or "UCL". 
                  If none of these options is correct, please write in an appropriate
                  value and the warning message will prompt editors to ensure that it is the correct value.
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <attList>
            <attDef ident="type" mode="change" usage="req">
              <desc>The <att>type</att> attribute on <gi>idno</gi> defines the kind of identifier contained in the text value.</desc>
              <valList mode="replace" type="closed">
                <valItem ident="accession-number"/>
                <valItem ident="catalog-number"/>
                <valItem ident="deprecated"/>
                <valItem ident="number"/>
                <valItem ident="project-number"/>
                <valItem ident="shelfmark"/>
                <valItem ident="URI"/>
                <valItem ident="URL"/>
                <valItem ident="URN"/>
              </valList>
            </attDef>
            <attDef ident="subtype" mode="change" usage="opt">
              <valList mode="replace" type="semi">
                <valItem ident="BAV"/>
                <valItem ident="Bekker"/>
                <valItem ident="Berlin"/>
                <valItem ident="BHS"/>
                <valItem ident="BHO"/>
                <valItem ident="BL"/>
                <valItem ident="BML"/>
                <valItem ident="BNF"/>
                <valItem ident="Cambridge"/>
                <valItem ident="CPG"/>
                <valItem ident="Crawford"/>
                <valItem ident="Fichtner"/>
                <valItem ident="Haddad-Isaac"/>
                <valItem ident="Harris"/>
                <valItem ident="Kühn"/>
                <valItem ident="Leiden"/>
                <valItem ident="Mingana"/>
                <valItem ident="Rosen"/>
                <valItem ident="Takashi"/>
                <valItem ident="Sachau"/>
                <valItem ident="SOAH"/>
                <valItem ident="Sinai"/>
              </valList>
            </attDef>
          </attList>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <!--<elementSpec ident="interpretation" module="header" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>-->
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="label" module="core" mode="change">
          <content>
            <sequence preserveOrder="true">
              <textNode/>
              <elementRef key="idno" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="ptr" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="1"/>
              <elementRef key="title" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="1"/>
            </sequence>
          </content>
          <constraintSpec ident="ptr-with-label" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:label[not(ancestor::tei:relation)]">
                <sch:report test="tei:ptr">
                  A &lt;ptr&gt; child of &lt;label&gt; should only be used
                  when &lt;label&gt; is the descendant of &lt;relation&gt;.
                </sch:report>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <constraintSpec ident="label-values" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/bibl/label[idno/@subtype='Bekker']">
                <sch:assert test="starts-with(., 'Bekker')">
                  This text should begin "Bekker". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/bibl/label[idno/@subtype='BML']">
                <sch:assert test="starts-with(., 'The Laurentian Library')">
                  This text should begin "The Laurentian Library". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/bibl/label[idno/@subtype='Fichtner']">
                <sch:assert test="starts-with(., 'Fichtner')">
                  This text should begin "Fichtner". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/bibl/label[idno/@subtype='HMML']">
                <sch:assert test="starts-with(., 'Hill Museum and Manuscript Library')">
                  This text should begin "Hill Museum and Manuscript Library". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/bibl/label[idno/@subtype='Kühn']">
                <sch:assert test="starts-with(., 'Kühn')">
                  This text should begin "Kühn". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/bibl/label[idno/@subtype='Rosen']">
                <sch:assert test="starts-with(., 'Rosen')">
                  This text should begin "Rosen". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/bibl/label[idno/@subtype='Takahashi']">
                <sch:assert test="starts-with(., 'Takahashi')">
                  This text should begin "Takahashi". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/bibl/label[idno/@subtype='UCL']">
                <sch:assert test="starts-with(., 'University College London')">
                  This text should begin "University College London". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/bibl/label[idno/@subtype='BAV']">
                <sch:assert test="starts-with(., 'Vatican Apostolic Library')">
                  This text should begin "The Vatican Apostolic Library". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <!--<attList>
            <attDef ident="subtype" mode="change">
              <valList type="closed">
                <valItem ident="book"/>
                <valItem ident="collection"/>
                <valItem ident="part"/>
              </valList>
            </attDef>
            <attDef ident="type" mode="change">
              <valList type="closed">
                <valItem ident="order"/>
              </valList>
            </attDef>
          </attList>-->
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <!--<elementSpec ident="langUsage" module="header" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>-->
        
        
        
        <!--<elementSpec ident="licence" module="header" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>-->
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="listBibl" module="core" mode="change">
          <content>
            <sequence preserveOrder="true">
              <elementRef key="head" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="1"/>
              <elementRef key="desc" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="1"/>
              <elementRef key="bibl" minOccurs="1" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
            </sequence>
          </content>
          <constraintSpec ident="listBibl-in-body" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:listBibl">
                <sch:assert test="tei:head">
                  This &lt;listBibl&gt; requires a &lt;head&gt;.
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:listBibl">
                <sch:assert test="tei:desc">
                  This &lt;listBibl&gt; requires a &lt;desc&gt;.
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:listBibl">
                <sch:assert test="@type">
                  This &lt;listBibl&gt; requires a @type attribute.
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <attList>
            <attDef ident="type" mode="change" usage="rec">
              <valList type="closed">
                <valItem ident="editions"/>
                <valItem ident="manuscripts"/>
                <valItem ident="modernTranslations"/>
                <valItem ident="ancientVersions"/>
                <valItem ident="secondaryLiterature"/>
              </valList>
            </attDef>
          </attList>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <!--<elementSpec ident="listRelation" module="namesdates" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>-->
        
        
        
        <!--<elementSpec ident="name" module="core" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>-->
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="note" module="core" mode="change">
          <content>
            <sequence preserveOrder="false">
              <textNode/>
              <elementRef key="date" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="persName" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="placeName" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="quote" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="1"/>
              <elementRef key="ref" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="1"/>
              <elementRef key="title" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
            </sequence>
          </content>
          <constraintSpec ident="noteGrp-note-type" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:noteGrp[@type='abstract']/tei:note">
                <sch:assert test="@type='abstract'">
                  This &lt;note&gt; must contain a @type attribute with value "abstract".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:noteGrp[@type='content']/tei:note">
                <sch:assert test="@type='content'">
                  This &lt;note&gt; must contain a @type attribute with value "abstract".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:noteGrp[@type='disambiguation']/tei:note">
                <sch:assert test="@type='disambiguation'">
                  This &lt;note&gt; must contain a @type attribute with value "abstract".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:noteGrp[@type='exerpts']/tei:note">
                <sch:assert test="@type='exerpt'">
                  This &lt;note&gt; must contain a @type attribute with value "abstract".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:noteGrp[@type='explicit']/tei:note">
                <sch:assert test="@type='explicit'">
                  This &lt;note&gt; must contain a @type attribute with value "abstract".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:noteGrp[@type='incipit']/tei:note">
                <sch:assert test="@type='incipit'">
                  This &lt;note&gt; must contain a @type attribute with value "abstract".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:noteGrp[@type='prologue']/tei:note">
                <sch:assert test="@type='prologue'">
                  This &lt;note&gt; must contain a @type attribute with value "abstract".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:noteGrp[@type='scope']/tei:note">
                <sch:assert test="@type='scope'">
                  This &lt;note&gt; must contain a @type attribute with value "abstract".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:noteGrp[@type='versions']/tei:note">
                <sch:assert test="@type='version'">
                  This &lt;note&gt; must contain a @type attribute with value "abstract".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <constraintSpec ident="quotes-in-notes" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="
                tei:body//tei:note[@type=('excerpt','explicit','incipit','prologue')]">
                <sch:assert test="tei:quote and count(*) = count(tei:quote)">
                  When &lt;note&gt; has type excerpt, explicit, incipit, or prologue,
                  it must contain only &lt;quote&gt; elements.
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <constraintSpec ident="listBibl-note-type" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:bibl/tei:listBibl//tei:note">
                <sch:report test="@type">
                  This &lt;note&gt; element does not take a @type attribute.
                </sch:report>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <attList>
            <attDef ident="type" mode="change" usage="rec">
              <valList mode="add" type="closed">
                <valItem ident="abstract">
                  <desc>A note containing a brief description of the work.</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="content">
                  <desc>A note containing a brief summary of the content of the work.</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="disambiguation">
                  <desc>A note containing a brief discussion of how to distinguish this 
                    work from others with which it has been or could be confused.</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="excerpt">
                  <desc>A note containing an exerpt from the work.</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="explicit">
                  <desc>A note containing the ending of the work.</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="incipit">
                  <desc>A note containing the beginning of the work.</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="licence">
                  <desc>A note containing the licence. Used only in the TEI header.</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="prologue">
                  <desc>A note containing the prologue of the work.</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="scope">
                  <desc>A note describing the works relationship to larger works 
                    or collections containing it.</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="version">
                  <desc>A note containing a brief summary of the versions of the work.</desc>
                </valItem>
              </valList>
            </attDef>
          </attList>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="noteGrp" module="core" mode="change">
          <content>
            <sequence preserveOrder="true">
              <elementRef key="desc" minOccurs="1" maxOccurs="1"/>
              <elementRef key="note" minOccurs="1" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
            </sequence>
          </content>
          <attList>
            <attDef ident="type" mode="change" usage="req">
              <valList type="closed">
                <valItem ident="abstract"/>
                <valItem ident="contents"/>
                <valItem ident="disambiguation"/>
                <valItem ident="excerpts"/>
                <valItem ident="explicit"/>
                <valItem ident="incipit"/>
                <valItem ident="prologue"/>
                <valItem ident="scope"/>
                <valItem ident="versions"/>
              </valList>
            </attDef>
          </attList>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="p" module="core" mode="change">
          
          <content>
            <sequence preserveOrder="false">
              <elementRef key="listBibl" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="1"/>
              <elementRef key="note" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="ref" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <textNode/>
            </sequence>
          </content>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="persName" module="namesdates" mode="change">
          <constraintSpec ident="ref-on-persName" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:persName[not(parent::tei:author)]">
                <sch:assert test="matches(@ref, concat('http://syriaca.org/person/', '\d+'))" role="error">
                  This &lt;persName&gt; element must take a @ref attribute 
                  with a Syriaca.org person URI which reqires 
                  the form 'http://syriaca.org/person/{\d+}' (where {\d+} is a number).
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <!--<elementSpec ident="profileDesc" module="header" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>
          
          
          
          <elementSpec ident="ptr" module="core" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>
          
          
          
          <elementSpec ident="publicationStmt" module="header" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>
          
          
          
          <elementSpec ident="ref" module="core" mode="change">
          <!-\- Not sure the @target attribute needs to be constrained. -\->
          
          </elementSpec>-->
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="relation" module="namesdates" mode="change">
          <constraintSpec ident="passive-values" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:relation">
                <sch:report test="contains(., '\s')">
                  The @passive attribute may only take one value.
                </sch:report>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <attList>
            <attDef ident="name" mode="delete"/>
            <attDef ident="ref" mode="change" usage="req">
              <valList type="closed">
                <valItem ident="dcterms:isPartOf"/>
                <valItem ident="dcterms:source"/>
                <valItem ident="skos:broader"/>
                <valItem ident="syriaca:commemorates"/>
                <valItem ident="syriaca:different-from"/>
              </valList>
            </attDef>
          </attList>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <!--<elementSpec ident="resp" module="core" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>
          
          
          
          <elementSpec ident="respStmt" module="core" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>
          
          
          
          <elementSpec ident="revisionDesc" module="header" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>-->
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="seriesStmt" module="header" mode="change">
          <constraintSpec ident="seriesStmt-series" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="//tei:seriesStmt//tei:title[@level='s']">
                <sch:assert test="
                  ./node() = 'A New Handbook of Syriac Literature' or 
                  ./node() = 'Gateway to the Syriac Saints'"> 
                  This &lt;title&gt; element must be "A New Handbook of Syriac Literature" or 
                  "Gateway to the Syriac Saints". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="//tei:seriesStmt[tei:title = 'A New Handbook of Syriac Literature']/tei:idno">
                <sch:assert test="matches(., 'http://syriaca.org/nhsl')">
                  This &lt;idno&gt; element must contain "http://syriaca.org/nhsl". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="//tei:seriesStmt[tei:title = 'Gateway to the Syriac Saints']/tei:idno">
                <sch:assert test="matches(., 'http://syriaca.org/saints')">
                  This &lt;idno&gt; element must contain "http://syriaca.org/saints". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <constraintSpec ident="seriesStmt-monograph" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="//tei:seriesStmt//tei:title[@level='m']">
                <sch:assert test="
                  ./node() = 'Bibliotheca Hagiographica Syriaca Electronica' or
                  ./node() = 'A Guide to the Bible in Syriac' or
                  ./node() = 'Syriac Scientific and Philosophical Literature'"> 
                  This &lt;title&gt; element must be 
                  "Bibliotheca Hagiographica Syriaca Electronica" or
                  "Guide to the Bible in Syriac" or 
                  "Syriac Scientific and Philosophical Literature". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="//tei:seriesStmt[tei:title = 'Bibliotheca Hagiographica Syriaca Electronica']/tei:idno">
                <sch:assert test="matches(., 'http://syriaca.org/bhse')">
                  This &lt;idno&gt; element must contain "http://syriaca.org/bhse". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="//tei:seriesStmt[tei:title='Bibliotheca Hagiographica Syriaca Electronica']">
                <sch:assert test="tei:biblScope/@n = '1'">
                  Requires a &lt;biblScope&gt; element with @n="1" since "Bibliotheca Hagiographica Syriaca Electronica" is volume 1 of 
                  "A New Handbook of Syriac Literature".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="//tei:seriesStmt[tei:title = 'A Guide to the Bible in Syriac']/tei:idno">
                <sch:assert test="matches(., 'http://syriaca.org/bible')">
                  This &lt;idno&gt; element must contain "http://syriaca.org/bible". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="//tei:seriesStmt[tei:title='A Guide to the Bible in Syriac']">
                <sch:assert test="tei:biblScope/@n = '2'">
                  Requires a &lt;biblScope&gt; element with @n="2" since "A Guide to the Bible in Syriac" is volume 2 of 
                  "A New Handbook of Syriac Literature".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <!--<elementSpec ident="sourceDesc" module="header" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>
          
          
          
          <elementSpec ident="sponsor" module="header" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>
          
          
          
          <elementSpec ident="taxonomy" module="header" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>
          
          
          
          <elementSpec ident="text" module="textstructure" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>-->
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="textLang" module="core" mode="change">
          <attList>
            <attDef ident="mainLang" mode="replace">
              <valList type="closed" mode="replace">
                <!-- Should this be ingested into the Taxonomy? We could we use keyword URIs instead of these. -->
                <valItem ident="ar">
                  <gloss>Arabic</gloss>
                  <desc>Arabic of any variety or period</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="ar-Syrc">
                  <gloss>Arabic—Garshuni</gloss>
                  <desc>Arabic Garshuni in unvocalized or undetermined Syriac script</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="ar-Syre">
                  <gloss>Arabic—Garshuni—Estrangela</gloss>
                  <desc>Arabic Garshuni in Estrangela Syriac script</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="ar-Syrj">
                  <gloss>Arabic—Garshuni—West Syriac</gloss>
                  <desc>Arabic Garshuni in vocalized West Syriac script</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="ar-Syrn">
                  <gloss>Arabic—Garshuni—East Syriac</gloss>
                  <desc>Arabic Garshuni in vocalized East Syriac script</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="cop">
                  <gloss>Coptic</gloss>
                  <desc>Coptic of any variety or period</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="cu">
                  <gloss>Slavonic—Old Church</gloss>
                  <desc>Old Church Slavonic</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="de">
                  <gloss>German</gloss>
                  <desc>German of any variety or period</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="el">
                  <gloss>Greek—Modern</gloss>
                  <desc>Modern Greek after A.D. 1453</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="en">
                  <gloss>English</gloss>
                  <desc>English of any variety or period</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="es">
                  <gloss>Spanish</gloss>
                  <desc>Spanish</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="fr">
                  <gloss>French</gloss>
                  <desc>French of any variety or period</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="gez">
                  <gloss>Ge'ez</gloss>
                  <desc>Ge'ez</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="grc">
                  <gloss>Greek—Ancient</gloss>
                  <desc>Ancient Greek to A.D. 1453</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="hy">
                  <gloss>Armenian</gloss>
                  <desc>Classical or Modern Armenian</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="it">
                  <gloss>Italian</gloss>
                  <desc>Italian</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="ka">
                  <gloss>Georgian</gloss>
                  <desc>Classical or Modern Georgian</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="la">
                  <gloss>Latin</gloss>
                  <desc>Latin of any variety or period</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="mal">
                  <gloss>Malayalam</gloss>
                  <desc>Malayalam of any variety or period</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="mal-Syrc">
                  <gloss>Malayalam—Garshuni</gloss>
                  <desc>Malayalam Garshuni in unvocalized or undetermined Syriac script</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="mal-Syre">
                  <gloss>Malayalam—Garshuni—Estrangela</gloss>
                  <desc>Malayalam Garshuni in Estrangela Syriac script</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="mal-Syrj">
                  <gloss>Malayalam—Garshuni—West Syriac</gloss>
                  <desc>Malayalam Garshuni in vocalized West Syriac script</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="mal-Syrn">
                  <gloss>Malayalam—Garshuni—East Syriac</gloss>
                  <desc>Malayalam Garshuni in vocalized East Syriac script</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="nl">
                  <gloss>Dutch</gloss>
                  <desc>Dutch</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="pt">
                  <gloss>Portuguese</gloss>
                  <desc>Portuguese</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="ru">
                  <gloss>Russian</gloss>
                  <desc>Russian</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="syr">
                  <gloss>Syriac</gloss>
                  <desc>Syriac of any variety or period</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="syr-Syre">
                  <gloss>Syriac—Estrangela script</gloss>
                  <desc>Syriac in Estrangela script</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="syr-Syrj">
                  <gloss>Syriac—West</gloss>
                  <desc>Syriac in vocalized West Syriac script</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="syr-Syrn">
                  <gloss>Syriac—East</gloss>
                  <desc>Syriac in vocalized East Syriac script</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="syr-pal">
                  <gloss>Christian Palestinian Aramaic</gloss>
                  <desc>Palestinian Aramaic written in Syriac script</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="syr-x-syrm">
                  <gloss>Syriac—Melkite script</gloss>
                  <desc>Syriac in Melkite script. Note: This is not an ISO code but a private use
                    code for Melkite employed by Syriaca.org until an ISO code is created</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="sog">
                  <gloss>Sogdian</gloss>
                  <desc>Sogdian</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="tr">
                  <gloss>Turkish</gloss>
                  <desc>Turkish</desc>
                </valItem>
              </valList>
            </attDef>
            <attDef ident="otherLangs" mode="replace">
              <valList type="closed" mode="replace">
                <!-- Should this be ingested into the Taxonomy? We could we use keyword URIs instead of these. -->
                <valItem ident="ar">
                  <gloss>Arabic</gloss>
                  <desc>Arabic of any variety or period</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="ar-Syrc">
                  <gloss>Arabic—Garshuni</gloss>
                  <desc>Arabic Garshuni in unvocalized or undetermined Syriac script</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="ar-Syre">
                  <gloss>Arabic—Garshuni—Estrangela</gloss>
                  <desc>Arabic Garshuni in Estrangela Syriac script</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="ar-Syrj">
                  <gloss>Arabic—Garshuni—West Syriac</gloss>
                  <desc>Arabic Garshuni in vocalized West Syriac script</desc>
